<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Rise Sharply / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The expected launch of big local investment trusts  
sent Japanese stock prices sharply higher today. The dollar fell 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 319.60 points,  
or 1.82 percent, to rebound from a four-day slump and close the day 
at 17,918.97. On Friday, the average closed down 66.92 points, or 
0.38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 111.04 yen, down 0.40 yen from late Friday in  
Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 111.56 yen on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened higher on buying by foreign  
investors. Domestic investors later joined in the buying spree, 
which came after the Nikkei average had fallen a total of 634.18 
points in the previous four trading days. 
</P>
<P>
	Short-term players bought actively, expecting that major local  
investment trusts will start buying Tuesday to set up funds 
totaling an estimated $541 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But some investors were taking a cautious approach, concerned  
about the impact of the yen's strength on the Japanese economy, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen makes Japanese goods more expensive overseas,  
hurting Japanese exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 19.56 points, or 1.32 percent, to 1,497.94. 
The TOPIX closed down 2.70 points, or 0.18 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 455.43 million shares, down from 487.04 million shares 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 693 to 492 on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while 120 issues were 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slid on selling by U.S. funds  
that let go of the currency in the belief that U.S. Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan seemed concerned about stock values. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at a Federal Reserve meeting on Friday, Greenspan  
said the extraordinary rise in U.S. stock prices over the last five 
years has been mostly inexplicable. Those remarks pushed the Dow 
Jones industrial average down. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow closed down 108.28 points, or 1 percent, to close at  
11,090.17 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Market players were also watching the outcome of a meeting of  
deputy finance ministers of the Group of Seven industrialized 
countries, scheduled for today and Tuesday in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 110.75 yen and 111.21 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.09 yen, down  
from 116.38 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.9800 percent from Friday's finish of 1.9400 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.33 yen from 99.66 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
