<HEADLINE> Voucher Supporters Raise Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Supporters of school vouchers have started a  
fund-raiser so first-year participants in the state's program can 
stay in private schools, despite a judge's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The School Choice Committee announced Monday it was trying to  
raise $2 million for Cleveland students who are new to the 
4-year-old program. The Ohio Roundtable, a public policy 
organization, donated $25,000 to the cause on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, U.S. District Judge Solomon Oliver Jr. altered his  
earlier ruling that halted the taxpayer-supported voucher program 
until he ruled on whether it violated the constitutional separation 
of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	He decided that students who participated in the program last  
year could get the vouchers again this year. New students could 
not. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 4,000 students from kindergarten through sixth-grade  
have signed up to get up to $2,500 in tuition vouchers for private 
schools in Cleveland. Court records show that 587 students were 
expected to join this year, but the School Choice Committee placed 
that number at 817. 
</P>
<P>
	The state attorney general's office and other pro-voucher groups  
have appealed the suspension of the program to federal court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
