<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Call Up Top Prospect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Vernon Wells, the Toronto Blue Jays' top  
prospect, was called up to the major leagues Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, 20, has quickly been promoted through the Blue Jays'  
organization this year. hitting .334 with 18 homers, 81 RBIs and 24 
steals with three farm team. 
</P>
<P>
	With Brian McRae hitting .175 and Jose Cruz Jr. in the minors,  
Toronto manager Jim Fregosi said Wells will play every day in 
center field. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've tried some guys there, and it just hasn't worked out,''  
Fregosi said. ``Wells hasn't missed a step wherever he's gone this 
year, so we'll see what we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells was the fifth pick overall in the 1997 amateur draft.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm here to help, whether it's to bring guys a glass of water,  
or to get a hit at a crucial time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto released outfielder Geronimo Berroa and optioned third  
baseman Casey Blake to the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Chris Carpenter, the Blue Jays most consistent  
starter this season, will miss his next start because of 
inflammation in his right elbow. Carpenter missed a few starts 
earlier this season because of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pain hasn't gotten to the point where I can't pitch,''  
Carpenter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelvim Escobar will replace him in the rotation.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
