<HEADLINE> Disney To Close ESPN Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. will close its three  
ESPN stores and focus on restaurants and the Internet to sell 
merchandise for the cable TV sports network, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney executives decided they can sell more product through the  
ESPN Zone restaurant and entertainment centers, the ESPNstore.com 
Internet site and through non-Disney retail stores, said Tom Park, 
executive vice president of The Disney Store Worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney will close ESPN-The Store sites in Glendale, Santa Ana  
and Torrance on Oct. 1. About 40 employees will be affected, with 
some being transferred to other Disney operations, according to a 
news statement Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The change comes in the midst of a companywide restructuring  
designed to reverse a long slump in Disney's profits and stock 
price. Weak sales of Disney merchandise have been among the 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney operates two ESPN Zone centers in Baltimore and Chicago.  
The company plans to open additional outlets in Atlanta, Washington 
and New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also plans to expand the ESPN.com Web site to  
include 15,000 new items, including golf and tennis equipment and 
footwear. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
