<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freeman Is Different Away From 'ER' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Yvette Freeman can do more than fix a fast IV  
on ``ER.'' She can belt out a song, make a movie and, Hollywood's 
expectations of a black actress aside, envision a future with a 
sunny prognosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman, who plays no-nonsense nurse Haleh Adams on NBC's  
popular medical drama, spent part of her off-duty summer months 
completing a recorded tribute to a woman she much admires, the late 
jazz singer Dinah Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	She practiced a new specialty as well after gaining entrance  
into an American Film Institute training program aimed at 
developing more women directors. 
</P>
<P>
	That Freeman is an accomplished singer may come as a surprise to  
``ER'' fans who have seen her only in scrubs. But she began her 
career on Broadway in the play ``Ain't Misbehavin''' and won a 1998 
Obie Award for ``Dinah Was,'' her off-Broadway musical based on 
Washington's life. 
</P>
<P>
	Her role as a filmmaker is one that seems a dream even to  
Freeman herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fabulous. It's so hard to get into this (AFI) program,  
and I got in this year. I'm so stoked. I'm a little scared and 
happy,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of eight women accepted out of a large pool of applicants,  
Freeman was given training, a camera and a portion of the money 
needed for her film. She assembled a production crew and the rest 
of the funding. 
</P>
<P>
	She's so pleased with the result, ``The Blessing Way,'' that she  
plans to submit it to the Sundance Film Festival. The film stars 
Michele Lamar Richards (``The Bodyguard'') and Darryl Alan Reed 
(who appeared with ``Freeman'' in ``Dinah Was'' and ``The American 
President''). 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a piece I wrote about a black family and the two ways of  
dealing in this society, being Afrocentric or going the 'corporate 
way,' the American way,'' said Freeman, who takes the position that 
``these two need to blend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we should separate. I think we should include  
our culture and be part of this society. But you come away from the 
movie with the two sides of the issue, and pull from it what you 
want,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	If filmmaking is her new love, music remains an old friend. The  
daughter of jazz pianist Charles Freeman, Yvette Freeman made her 
name on stage with her rich, supple voice, able to handle blues and 
ballads with equal ease. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Tribute to Dinah Washington,'' her first recording, was  
produced by Freeman with her husband, jazz pianist and arranger 
Lanny Hartley. The pair work together at home -- in separate 
offices, Freeman notes -- in sweet harmony. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the songs they chose for the CD are ``Come Rain or Come  
Shine,'' ``A Bad Case of the Blues'' and ``My Foolish Heart.'' 
Missing is the popular Washington tune ``What a Diff'rence a Day 
Makes''; Freeman is saving that for a planned ``Dinah Was'' disc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her songs are fabulous songs. They're songs with stories. And,  
since I'm an actress first, I sing the story. ... She tried to tell 
the story, and that's what I picked up on. It's the acting of the 
song, yet it's the emotion that's getting across in the music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman's admiration for Washington extends beyond her indelible  
talent. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a businesswoman, had her own company and produced  
other singers. That was something unheard of in the '50s for a 
woman -- and she was a black woman,'' Freeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such career control is worth emulating. ``You can't just be an  
artist off in the corner somewhere. If you don't know about the 
business, it's not going to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The television industry's current disinterest in ethnic  
characters makes it even more vital for minority performers to take 
an active role in creating jobs for themselves and others, Freeman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics have blasted the major broadcast networks for fielding a  
nearly all-white slate of new programs for the fall. The focus on 
young performers also is disturbing, said Freeman, who surveyed the 
new series' scripts and found only a single role she could play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's horrible. This season is horrible. I think everybody just  
got a little mixed up because we were on our way to diversity. ... 
This country is pushing toward diversity, and I don't know what 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the reasons, Freeman said, she's confident the  
situation will change. And she intends to help force the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I have a place, I have something to do. And it's not  
only me: Every woman, every ethnic type, needs to come up with 
product for Hollywood. ... It's going to come from us. We've got to 
be ready to produce projects, give the powers that be ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the powers that be have to remember about who's in this  
country. TV's gotta keep up.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	BIG GAME: Turns out Animal Planet's most popular series is ``The  
Crocodile Hunter,'' featuring Steve and Terri Irwin. To satisfy 
fans, the channel has deemed this the official ``Crocodile Hunter 
Week,'' featuring new adventures with crocs and more. Among the 
episodes: tonight's ``Africa's Deadliest Snakes,'' in which Steve 
Irwin fulfills his dream of tracking some of the world's most 
remarkable snakes, and ``Wild River of Africa'' on Tuesday, which 
includes a trip down Zambia's Luangwa River. The series shows at 8 
p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
