<DOCNO> APW19990830.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 07:52:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injuries Take Toll on NFL Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	St. Louis lost its starting quarterback for the season, and the  
NFL might have seen the last of one of football's most intense 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night's exhibition games provided trainers around the  
league with plenty of work, as a number of players went down with 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis Rams quarterback Trent Green tore the anterior  
cruciate ligament in his left knee, sustained a third-degree sprain 
of the medial collateral ligament and also had cartilage damage in 
a 24-21 victory over San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland linebacker Chris Spielman could announce his  
retirement today after sustaining a ``stinger'' during the Browns' 
35-24 win over Chicago when he was blindsided by Bears center Casey 
Wiegmann while trying to cut back on a screen play. 
</P>
<P>
	Other significant players injured in Saturday night's games were  
New Orleans starting quarterback Billy Joe Hobert, Miami running 
Cecil Collins and New York Giants center Brian Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Reconstructive surgery on Green's knee will be scheduled when  
the swelling subsides in about 2-3 weeks. Dr. Robert Shively, the 
Rams' physician, estimated the recovery period at 13 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury occurred when Chargers strong safety Rodney Harrison,  
blitzing on the play, lunged at the back of Green's knees just 
after a pass was thrown. Green completed all 11 of his attempts 
before the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it was gone,'' Green said. ``I just felt it grind and  
snap. I heard the whole thing. It was a very uncomfortable 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Warner, an NFL Europe and Arena Football League veteran who  
has just one quarter of NFL experience, became St. Louis' starter 
by default. The team also acquired Paul Justin from Oakland as 
insurance Sunday, giving up a seventh-round pick in next year's 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielman, attempting a comeback from neck fusion surgery in  
1997, might retire after a violent helmet-on-helmet collision sent 
him to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	After shedding and spinning off one blocker, Spielman turned and  
before he could get his feet planted, Wiegmann crushed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielman stayed on the ground for several moments, and later  
told Cleveland offensive tackle Lomas Brown, who also played with 
him in Detroit, that he had been momentarily paralyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's exploring all of his options,'' said Browns coach Chris  
Palmer, who spoke to Spielman twice on Sunday. ``He's going to look 
at everything and go from there. What we want to do is sit back 
take a look at things, let things settle down for 24 hours both 
emotionally and physically and then talk about the subject at that 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He got a scare in training camp when he was blasted by fullback  
Tarek Saleh, a blow that sent him to the hospital for an MRI. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago lost backup defensive tackle Jimmy Herndon for the  
season with a torn ACL in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobert is expected to miss the Saints' final preseason game  
after fracturing one of his ribs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobert completed 10 of 15 passes for 179 yards and two  
touchdowns before a helmet to his right side fractured the rib. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shouldn't be that big a deal,'' Hobert said, although he  
admitted he was in pain just standing still. ``If they wanted me to 
play in the next game, I could as long as I wore a protective rib 
vest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints plan to hold Hobert out of Thursday's preseason game  
against Tennessee and have him ready for the opener against 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami was relieved to learn tests showed Collins had no break in  
his injured right ankle, giving him a chance to heal for the season 
opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, the Dolphins' fifth-round draft pick, will be on  
crutches for a few days and miss Thursday's game at Green Bay. 
There's a possibility he could be ready when Miami opens the season 
Sept. 13 at Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad it wasn't serious,'' said Collins, who leads the team  
with 34 carries and 144 yards. ``I'm going to work hard with the 
trainers to do everything I can to try and get ready as soon as 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI exam showed Collins aggravated an injury Collins  
sustained two years ago at LSU. Collins broke his right leg and 
damaged ankle ligaments in an October 1997 game against Vanderbilt. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, attempting a comeback after missing two seasons with  
an eye injury, sprained his left knee in the first half of a 16-10 
loss to the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' injury doesn't appear to be that serious, coach Jim  
Fassel said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The veteran center had an MRI and there appears to be no  
structural damage. While Fassel is optimistic, he would not say 
when Williams will be back until he speaks with Dr. Russell Warren, 
the team's orthopedic surgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	In other training camp news:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Redskins    	
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative on Dan Wilkinson's dislocated left ring  
finger. The defensive tackle is not expected to miss any practice 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive end Kenard Lang could be out for a week after  
spraining an ankle. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Eagles    	
</P>
<P>
	Starting quarterback Doug Pederson said he should be back on the  
field the next day or so after suffering a lower back contusion in 
the third quarter of Thursday's 17-13 loss to the Minnesota 
Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels great,'' Pederson said following treatment on his  
back Sunday. ``I took today off to help it heal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson was hit in the back by a Vikings linebacker when he  
jumped on the ground after scrambling with the ball. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Ravens    	
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore isn't making much headway in their contract talks with  
Pro Bowl defensive end Michael McCrary, who reportedly left the 
team over the weekend after discussions over a possible extension 
reached an impasse. The Ravens, however, insisted that McCrary 
never informed them of that decision. 
</P>
<P>
	McCrary underwent offseason knee surgery and wasn't supposed to  
play Saturday anyway. The players were given Sunday off, so McCrary 
won't be considered AWOL until today, when he is scheduled to begin 
practice for Friday's exhibition finale against the New York 
Giants. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Panthers    	
</P>
<P>
	Carolina waived linebacker Horace Cook, defensive tackles  
Chartric Darby and Jerome Davis, offensive tackle Jeffrey Flowe, 
wide receiver Terry Guess, offensive guard Michael Lies, linebacker 
Sam Manuel, defensive end Andre Slappey and running back Reggie 
Shufford. 
</P>
