<HEADLINE> American To Integrate Reno Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines is merging Reno Air  
Inc. into its system today, about eight months after the nation's 
second-largest airline purchased the low-cost carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	American's parent company, AMR Corp., met with its pilots on  
Monday in a last-minute attempt to work out a deal over how the 
merger would occur. No details were released on the results of the 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have disagreed over how pilots would be integrated  
into the company since Fort Worth, Texas-based American bought tiny 
Reno last December. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute evolved into a pilot sickout in February that  
stranded hundreds of thousands of passengers all over the world and 
cost the company $225 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Allied Pilots Association and American continued to  
negotiate since the illegal job action, but were unable to reach a 
solution. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the sticking points in the deal was protocol for any  
future acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to conclude deals with two other unions  
relatively quickly, but after more than nine months of negotiation 
and mediation we are still without an agreement with APA,'' Robert 
Baker, executive vice president of operations, wrote to the 
company's 9,500 pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	American's integration plan brings former Reno pilots into the  
company at the bottom of the seniority list. That means lower-paid 
Reno pilots will get a boost in their salaries, but they will have 
less say in their flying schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, a dozen American pilots who underwent training in July  
will now hold captain jobs formerly held by their Reno 
counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the union has been reminding the pilots that they  
must not repeat the February sickout. That illegal job action 
resulted in a federal judge holding the union in contempt when his 
order to return to work was ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	During talks with the judge, the APA agreed to a permanent  
injunction barring the union and its members from any future 
actions -- strike, sickout or slowdown. That decision leaves the 
union with no recourse but to ultimately accept American's decision 
to go forward with integration, according to observers. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has e-mailed its members that U.S. District Judge Joe  
Kendall's order remains in effect and that the APA must comply. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also ordered the pilots' union to pay a $45 million  
judgment as punishment for the sickout. The union has promised an 
appeal of the massive award, which is larger than the union's net 
worth. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
