<HEADLINE> Kenyan Admits Fixing Track Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Bernard Barmasai lost his shot at a share  
of the $1 million Golden League jackpot today for saying he had 
colluded with a countryman to determine the result of a race. 
</P>
<P>
	An International Amateur Athletic Federation panel ruled  
Barmasai put ``athletics into disrepute'' by saying he had asked 
fellow Kenyan Christopher Koskei not to challenge his lead late in 
the 3,000-meter steeplechase at the Aug. 11 Weltklasse meet in 
Zurich, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The sport's world governing body considered stripping Barmasai  
of his victory in the race but let it stand, saying there was not 
enough evidence of collusion between the two runners. 
</P>
<P>
	Barmasai, the world-record holder in the steeplechase, said  
after winning at Zurich that he had spoken to Koskei during the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `Leave it for me,' and that's why he slowed down,''  
Barmasai said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision was taken on the basis of the code of conduct.  
One of these rules states that an athlete who puts athletics into 
disrepute can be sanctioned in some way,'' IAAF spokesman Giorgio 
Reineri said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barmasai had been one of four athletes still in contention for  
the Golden League jackpot, which is split among those who go 
unbeaten through the seven biggest Grand Prix meets on the circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	American sprinter Marion Jones, 800-meter record-holder Wilson  
Kipketer, and distance runner Gabriela Szabo are still alive for at 
least a share of the $1 million jackpot with two meets remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, though, injured her back in Seville and is likely out for  
the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Koskei took the steeplechase gold medal at the World  
Championships last week. Barmasai finished fifth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
