<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Says Job Prospects Are Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. demand for workers continues at the highest  
level in two decades, with employment especially strong in the 
wholesale and retail trades in advance of Christmas, according to a 
new survey. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarterly survey of some 16,000 companies by Manpower Inc.  
indicated that 30 percent planned further hiring in the 
October-December quarter. Just 8 percent anticipated cutbacks, 
while 58 percent said they expected no change. The remaining 4 
percent were unsure, according to the survey, which is being 
released Monday by the nation's largest temporary staffing 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth-quarter figures are slightly weaker than the  
July-September quarter, when 32 percent of those responding 
expected to be hiring. But when adjusted for seasonal variations, 
prospects for job seekers are actually improved, Manpower said. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings by Manpower suggest that strong job creation should  
continue to hold U.S. unemployment in check. The nation's 
unemployment rate has been at or below 4.5 percent for more than a 
year, the best showing in three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey results have been strong for three years, said  
Jeffrey Joerres, president and chief executive of Manpower, which 
is based in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't seen an unbroken trend of this length since the  
1976-79 period,'' he said in a statement released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the latest quarter's figures, we can clearly see that the  
labor market will be going into the new millennium roaring. As we 
look into the year 2000, we see no slowdown from a demand 
perspective,'' he added in an earlier interview with The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited ``the critical need for holiday help'' as the  
reason that the strongest demand in the fourth quarter is expected 
in wholesale and retail industries. 
</P>
<P>
	It said 40 percent of wholesalers and retailers expected to  
increase hiring. Forty-eight percent said they saw no change, 8 
percent anticipated a decrease and the rest said they didn't know. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures suggest that retail companies ``are very optimistic  
about what is coming up'' this holiday season, Joerres said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest survey, companies in Western states anticipated  
the most hiring, followed by the Midwest, South and Northeast, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Manpower said its survey was based on telephone interviews with  
companies in 484 U.S. cities. The results have a margin of error of 
plus or minus 2 percentage points. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 17:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clintons Visit New York State Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- They could have been any couple stepping  
up to a taffy stand at the New York State Fair. ``Let's get a 
variety pack!'' the wife said, as the husband pulled a wad of bills 
from his pants pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	But with television news cameras rolling, the proprietor  
wouldn't hear of taking $6.95 from President Clinton and his wife, 
all-but-declared Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton, whose 
visit to the fair seemed like a perfect campaign moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Adoring crowds stood by the corn dog and sausage stands to  
glimpse the couple, who shook hands, posed for pictures and signed 
autographs for nearly two hours under sunny skies. 
</P>
<P>
	At the dairy exhibit, Mrs. Clinton and daughter Chelsea stopped  
at the front counter, where Mrs. Clinton invited reporters and 
photographers to glasses of milk. ``Anybody else?'' a beaming Mrs. 
Clinton asked. ``Chocolate or white?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She had good reason to be beaming. It seemed that well-wishers  
were everywhere she turned during the first family's first vacation 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the road to Skaneatles, where the Clintons will spend the  
remainder of their vacation on a borrowed estate, they stopped at a 
lemonade stand where two boys waved a sign promising them free 
refreshments. 
</P>
<P>
	Up the road, three dozen people waited to greet them. After  
winding another boy's camera to make sure he got the shot, the 
president shook hands and stepped back into his bronze Suburban. 
</P>
<P>
	But the motorcade wasn't ready to roll. Clinton waited with his  
arms folded, chin in hand, and admired his wife as she chatted with 
the young girls who stepped up to greet her and shook every last 
hand in the line. 
</P>
<P>
	It was as if he was sizing up the family's next political star.  
Asked what advice he had for her, he said, ``I think she's doing 
pretty well without any help from me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, in fact, has had plenty of help from her husband.  
</P>
<P>
	The family vacation in the Hamptons on Long Island, the Finger  
Lakes region of upstate New York and Martha's Vineyard off the 
coast of Massachusetts included several fund-raisers for the 
Democratic party and Mrs. Clinton's own exploratory committee. New 
York is one of the states where the president is most popular. 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving at the Syracuse airport, more than 2,500 cheering  
well-wishers greeted the Clintons. One woman held a sign saying 
``Clinton for Senate.'' Others offered notecards, flowers, babies 
to hold, and pressed forward for pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	At Mrs. Clinton's side along the rope line was Mike Bragman, the  
influential majority leader of the state assembly. The president 
and first lady addressed an annual luncheon hosted by the state 
comptroller, where Clinton renewed his call for using the federal 
budget surplus to shore up the retirement system. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton compared America's good economic times to ``farmers  
sitting on a good crop'' and trying to decide how best to build on 
the bounty. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're at the state fair, you need to think like that,''  
Clinton said. ``If America is a farm, and we're the farm family, 
and we've had years of great crops and we've got a lot of money in 
the bank, what are we going to do with it?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
