<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prevention Said Key in Handling HIV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With life-prolonging drugs proving to be  
successful in reducing the number of AIDS-related deaths, more 
efforts to control the epidemic should be directed toward 
prevention, health officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,000 scientists, doctors, researchers and advocates  
are in Atlanta this week for the National HIV Prevention Conference 
-- the first national conference addressing efforts to monitor and 
prevent the spread of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have demonstrated that prevention works and deserves  
support,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Koplan, head of the Centers for Disease 
Control and Prevention. ``Nevertheless, as in most areas of public 
health, support for prevention is frequently more rhetorical than 
substantive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest national data on trends in HIV infections and AIDS  
deaths were expected to be released today. Also, researchers will 
release the results of studies using a new antibody test that 
allows scientists to measure the time of new HIV infections with 
much greater precision. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1980s, more than 300,000 have died of AIDS. The good  
news is that the number of new HIV infections has dropped from 
about 100,000 a year to 40,000. However, federal health officials 
warned Sunday about a growing complacency about HIV, especially 
among some people most at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's becoming increasingly difficult to get people to pay  
attention to HIV prevention and that in and of itself is a primary 
reason for this conference,'' said Dr. Helene Gayle, director of 
the CDC's National Center for HIV, STD, and TB Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite a growing complacency about the need for HIV  
prevention, HIV remains a serious disease that is still very much 
with us and there is a greater need for HIV prevention today more 
than ever,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference, which ends Wednesday, also will examine the  
disproportionate effect the epidemic is having on women and 
minorities, especially blacks who are becoming infected with AIDS 
at record rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid 1980s, blacks represented about 25 percent of the new  
cases of AIDS reported, Hispanics about 14 percent and women 8 
percent, U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher said. By 1997-98, 
blacks made up 45 percent of the cases, Hispanics 22 percent and 
women 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the major concerns we have about the AIDS epidemic is  
that increasingly it is affecting communities that tend to be left 
out of the health care and public health system,'' Satcher said. 
``We know that in order to be successful we have to find a new way 
to reach these communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conference was organized by the CDC and other sponsoring  
organizations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
