<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 00:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Kid's in the Title Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Jose Santos knew the final result  
of the Travers as Lemon Drop Kid carried him into the final turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the race won since the half-mile pole,'' the jockey  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until just inside the sixteenth pole that Lemon Drop  
Kid got ahead of Vision and Verse and beat him to the wire by 
three-quarters of a length Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Santos' second win in a $1 million Grade I stakes on Lemon Drop  
Kid -- he beat Vision and Verse by a nose in the Belmont Stakes -- 
put Lemon Drop Kid into the Horse of the Year picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's shown he should be one of the top 3-year-olds,'' Santos  
said after Lemon Drop Kid beat seven rivals, including favored 
Menifee, third another 1 3/4 lengths back, at the end of the 1 1/4 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Scotty Schulhofer, Lemon Drop Kid's 73-year-old Hall of Fame  
trainer, isn't claiming any honors yet for the colt. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a lot to do yet,'' Scotty Schulhofer said. ``He's  
going to have to beat Behrens and some older horses to get Horse of 
the Year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for now, however, Lemon Drop Kid is a serious contender for  
the 3-year-old title. Still in the hunt for that championship is 
Charismatic, the Kentucky Derby-Preakness winner, who was retired 
after being injured while finishing third in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont on 
June 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid will run next in the 1 1/4-mile Jockey Club Gold Cup  
on Oct. at Belmont Park, then in the 1 1/4-mile Breeders' Cup Classic 
on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park. Both Grade I stakes are 
weight-for-age races. 
</P>
<P>
	He probably would meet the 5-year-old Behrens, leader of the  
handicap division, in the Gold Cup and the Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an improving horse, and I'm not sure where we'll go  
next,'' said Bill Mott, trainer of Vision and Verse. Mott's 
Unbridled Jet finished last. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Elliott Walden said he didn't know what Menifee's next  
race would be, but co-owner James Stone of New Orleans indicated he 
would like to see the colt start in the 1 1/4-mile Super Derby on Oct. 
2 at Louisiana Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	The stretch-running Menifee was trapped on the rail by Unbridled  
Jet in the run down the backstretch. The Derby-Preakness runnerup's 
chances also were compromised by a slow pace. The fractions were 24 
seconds for the quarter, 48 1/4 for the half and 1:12 2-5 for 
three-quarters. Lemon Drop Kid's winning time was 2:02 under scale 
weight of 126 pounds on a fast track. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Lemon Drop Kid's five wins in 13 career starts have  
been in Grade I stakes -- he won Belmont's Futurity last year -- and 
he also has three seconds and two thirds. The $600,000 winner's 
purse boosted his earnings to $1.541,470. He paid a winning mutuel 
of $9.30. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope he gets a little credit now,'' Santos said. ``He had to  
prove he was the real thing. I have to give all the credit to 
Scotty Schulhofer. He's done a wonderful job with this horse. He 
told me he had the horse 110 percent, and he was right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schulhofer decided not to push Lemon Drop Kid because he was a  
May foal. When he finished ninth in the Kentucky Derby, it was only 
his third start of the year. The colt was held out of the 
Preakness, then won the Belmont and finished second in the Jim 
Dandy on Aug. 8 at Saratoga on a sloppy track, a surface he did not 
like, before winning the Travers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecton Park, the Jim Dandy winner and Menifee's stablemate,  
finished fourth in the Travers and was followed by Best of Luck, 
Badger Gold, Cat Thief and Unbridled Jet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
