<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 176.04  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today as bond yields rose  
and investors, seeking clues to the future course of interest 
rates, braced for another round of economic data. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 176.04 at 10,914.13. The Dow has 
fallen more than 100 points in each of the last three sessions. 
Broader stock indicators also fell. But trading volume was very 
light, which tends to exaggerate price moves. The Nasdaq composite 
index fell 46.20 to 2,712.70. Investors remained nervous about 
interest rates as they awaited reports this week on manufacturing 
activity and unemployment, which are expected to offer some 
evidence of how fast the U.S. economy is growing, and whether 
inflation is escalating. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,914.13   - 176.04
NYSE Issues:         Advances  840  Declines 2137  Unchgd  535
NYSE Volume:         575,804,530
Most Active NYSE issue:         Republic Svcs11 1/8   - 5 3/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1322.30 - 25.97
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          775.22    -  7.30
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,712.70   - 46.20
Gold(final) -    $254.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   $5.100  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	New Home Sales Rise in July  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New home sales rose a tiny 0.1 percent in July  
but still managed to post the second-highest level ever, a sign 
that the housing sector continues to thrive despite rising mortgage 
rates. The Commerce Department reported today that sales were up in 
all parts of the country in July except for the West. The Northeast 
led way with a 33.9 percent increase. Low unemployment and higher 
wages and benefits are helping sales, but economists also suggest 
that some people are jumping off the fence to lock in a deal now 
before mortgage rates climb further. They figure they can refinance 
their homes if rates fall. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Lower Overall  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) --Plans for a major French supermarket merger pushed  
the European retail sector higher, but shares overall were lower 
today. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed 
down 0.4 point at 314.57, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, 
which tracks 297 companies in countries joining the single 
currency, ended down 0.6 point at 329.34. France's CAC-40 index of 
most actively traded French stocks rose 0.3 percent. The Dow Jones 
Euro Stoxx 50 Index finished down 15.7 points at 3,837.8, while the 
DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 14.1 points at 3,775.5. Among 
domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra Dax closed down 27.83 points, 
or 0.5 percent, at 5,392.53, while Amsterdam's AEX ended down 0.53 
points at 584.36 points. London's market was closed for a bank 
holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	French Retailers Plan Merger  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French supermarket group Carrefour said today it  
was acquiring rival Promodes in a deal that would create the 
world's second-largest retailer and a European challenge to 
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. The friendly stock deal valued at about $16.3 
billion was expected to prompt similar mergers across Europe, where 
retailers are scrambling to find partners as Wal-Mart seeks to 
expand on the Continent. The combined operation will have a market 
capitalization of about $49 billion and annual sales of nearly $50 
billion. But it will still be much smaller than Wal-Mart, which had 
sales of $138 billion in 1998 and is expected to easily surpass 
that figure this year. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Cuts Long-Distance Rates  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. today took steps to meet a price war  
that has been hurting revenues. It announced that it is cutting 
prices for long-distance phone calls to 7 cents a minute and 
simplifying rates. The rate is still higher than offers introduced 
early this month from MCI WorldCom and Sprint. The new AT&AMP;T rate is 
good for calls made any time. Customers who want the rate also must 
pay the company a fee of $5.95 a month. AT&AMP;T had charged 15 cents a 
minute around the clock with no monthly fee or 10 cents a minute 
with a $4.95 fee. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Sets Economic Growth Goal  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government is aiming for 5 percent  
average annual economic growth over the next eight to 10 years, the 
Economics Ministry said in a report released today. The report, 
carried by the ITAR-Tass news agency, gave no details on how the 
government plans to achieve that somewhat optimistic goal. Russia's 
economy has contracted for each of the past 10 years with the 
exception of 1997, when it grew by 0.4 percent. The economy is 
forecast to contract by 2 percent this year. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF Loans to Russia Said OK  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund has seen no  
evidence that its loans to Russia have been diverted through U.S. 
banks, a senior IMF official said today, noting the organization 
has already put tight controls in place to prevent such illegal 
actions. The comments by Tom Dawson, director of external affairs 
at the international lending agency, followed a statement by the 
Chairman Jim Leach, R-Iowa, of the House Banking Committee. He said 
that IMF loans to Russia should be halted until controls are put in 
place to prevent diversions of the sort that reportedly occurred 
through Bank of New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan's Auto Production Falls  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's auto production fell for the fourth month  
in a row in July, registering a 3.6 percent decline from a year 
earlier. A total of 887,288 cars, trucks and buses rolled off the 
assembly lines last month, compared with 920,776 a year ago, the 
Japan Automobile Manufacturers' Association said. It blamed 
continued sluggish consumer demand for big-ticket items and falling 
exports. 

</P>
<P>
	Thais See 3 Pct. GDP Growth  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's economy and currency, which  
triggered Asia's financial crisis, will grow stronger in 2000 after 
recovering this year, economic ministers were told today. The 
National Economic and Social Development Board, a state planning 
agency, forecast gross domestic product would grow by 3 percent in 
2000. The International Monetary Fund has predicted growth of 
between 3 and 4 percent for 1999. 

</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen, Audi Recall 428,000 Cars  
</P>
<P>
	WOLFSBURG, Germany (AP) -- Volkswagen and its Audi subsidiary are  
recalling about 428,000 cars worldwide, all produced in the first 
half of 1998, due to a potential problem with the steering 
mechanism. The recall includes 270,000 VW Passats and 158,000 Audi 
A4, A6 and A8 cars, said VW spokesman Jens Bobsien. VW is sending 
letters to car owners instructing them to go to their dealer or 
mechanic to get the problem fixed at no charge as a precautionary 
measure. There have been no known accidents as a result of the 
problem, Bobsien said. 

</P>
