<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Futures Up on Output Decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures jumped sharply Monday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange after three leading world oil producers decided 
against raising production. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas and gasoline futures also rose. In other markets,  
coffee futures plummeted to a five-and-a-half-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude and its products advanced sharply after Venezuela, Mexico  
and Saudi Arabia announced over the weekend after a meeting of 
their oil ministers in Caracas that production cuts aimed at 
lowering supplies and raising prices will be kept in place through 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	The three countries agreed to a first round of cuts in March  
1998 and a second round last March. 
</P>
<P>
	The market had been watching the Caracas meeting closely for any  
hint that production would be boosted at next month's meeting of 
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna. 
Venezuela and Saudi Arabia are OPEC members. 
</P>
<P>
	The price jump for oil futures was the third in a row after the  
market was jolted last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also contributing to Monday's rally was the impact of three  
refinery shutdowns in recent days that raised concern about fuel 
supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisiana officials confirmed Monday that Chalmette Refining, a  
70,000-barrel-a-day joint venture, will be shut down for as long as 
two and a half weeks after unexpected problems closed it on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips Petroleum shut a refinery that produces low-sulfur  
diesel and kerosene fuels the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, a fire closed down a 75,000-barrel-a-day Sunoco  
refinery in Toledo, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Morris, an analyst for Paine Webber, said the natural gas  
rise came in response to the runup in crude futures. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for October delivery rose 4.7 cents to $2.969 per  
each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	October crude rose 74 cents to $22.01 a barrel; September  
heating oil rose 1.34 cents to 57.33 cents a gallon; September 
unleaded gas rose 2.71 cents to 68.82 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices sank as investors reacted to ample supplies on the  
market, with Brazil's harvest winding down after suffering little 
frost damage and truck strikes in Brazil and Colombia this week 
causing no impact. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's harvest has been aided by recent dry weather, and  
analysts say the next crop is expected to be significantly larger. 
Rain also has boosted prospects for the fall harvest in Colombia. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
