<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Industrial Output Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese industrial production fell 0.6 percent in  
July from the month before, the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires had projected on  
average that industrial production would be up 0.2 percent from 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	The industrial production figure is calculated after adjustment  
for seasonal factors. 
</P>
<P>
	MITI also said that it expects production in August and  
September to show increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Output will surge 4.7 percent in August from July on an  
anticipated increase in the shipping of electronic machinery, 
Ministry official Naoki Nakajima said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry expects output to increase 0.2 percent in  
September, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has been fighting its worst economic downturn in more than  
50 years. But some bright signs have appeared recently, most 
notably a 2.0 percent increase in gross domestic product for the 
first quarter of this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
