<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Give Back Some Gains / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell for a third straight session  
Monday, sending yields back over 6 percent, as a report about 
strong housing sales fanned inflation fears. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 3/32  
point, or $10.93 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.05 percent from 5.97 percent 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported Monday that new home sales rose  
to their second highest level on record in July. New home sales 
climbed 0.1 percent in July to an annual rate of 980,000, second 
only to November 1998's blistering annual pace of 985,000. That was 
faster than economists had forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong demand for housing shows consumer spending still at a  
fast pace, which worries traders because it might cause the Federal 
Reserve to increase interest rates for a third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices had soared in the past week on expectations that the  
Federal Reserve would let interest rates stabilize for the rest of 
this year. But on Thursday, after the Fed had raised short-term 
rates to rein in inflation, bond traders began to re-evaluate 
whether yields had fallen too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates push down prices for bonds, which pay a  
fixed rate of return. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell 1/8 point to 5/32 point, and intermediate maturities fell 12/32 
point to 11/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.98 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.85 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.18 percent, as the discount rose 0.08 percentage 
point to 4.98 percent. One-year yields were 5.28 percent as the 
discount rose 0.04 percentage point from late Friday to 5.01 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.31 1/4 percent from 5.25 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 5/16 point to 114 16/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.77 percent, up from 5.75 percent late 
Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
