<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	E. Timorese Vote on Independence  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Throngs of eager East Timorese were  
waiting outside polling stations when they opened today to vote on 
whether their troubled territory should become independent. Despite 
months of concern that people might be too afraid to vote in the 
U.N.-sponsored referendum, long lines formed peacefully outside 
polling centers in the territorial capital, Dili. The historic 
referendum was the first time East Timor's people have had a direct 
say in how their homeland should be governed after almost four 
centuries of Portuguese colonial rule and 24 years of iron-fisted 
Indonesian occupation. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Ends Fund-Raising Weekend  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton wound up a New York  
weekend devoted to fund raising for Democrats with a plug for one 
Democrat in particular -- his wife. ``Of all the people I have ever 
known in public life, the ablest, the smartest, the most 
passionately dedicated and committed, is the person who wants to be 
the next United States senator from New York,'' Clinton said at a 
fund-raising dinner last night on Long Island. Officially, Hillary 
Rodham Clinton is only exploring a run in New York in 2000, but the 
president's words were just one clue that she intends to go ahead 
with the campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Dennis Brings Rain, Winds to Carolina Coast  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C. (AP) -- The punch-packing heart of Hurricane  
Dennis continued to track parallel to the Carolina coast today, 
while its edge brought pelting rain, strong winds and the threat of 
beachfront flooding. Forecasters expected the storm to turn 
northeast away from land, but the possibility of a full-force 
landfall in North Carolina remained. Even if Dennis' eye remains 
offshore, they said, the storm's strong winds could cause problems 
for coastal residents. A hurricane warning was in effect for much 
of the North Carolina coast, and a smattering of residents sought 
refuge in shelters in several coastal counties. 

</P>
<P>
	Furrow May Get Good Representation  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Although he didn't have enough money to hire  
his own lawyer, Buford O. Furrow Jr. may still have ended up with 
the best representation he could have hoped for. Furrow -- the white 
supremacist who allegedly confessed to shooting up a Jewish 
community center full of children, then killing a Filipino-American 
postman, is a client of the federal public defender's office. That 
office has declined comment on what strategy it will use for 
Furrow, who faces a post-indictment arraignment today in the 
killing of postman Joseph Ileto. 

</P>
<P>
	Prevention Said Key in Handling HIV  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With life-prolonging drugs proving to be  
successful in reducing the number of AIDS-related deaths, more 
efforts to control the epidemic should be directed toward 
prevention, health officials say. More than 2,000 scientists, 
doctors, researchers and advocates are in Atlanta this week for the 
National HIV Prevention Conference -- the first national conference 
addressing efforts to monitor and prevent the spread of HIV, the 
virus that causes AIDS. The latest national data on trends in HIV 
infections and AIDS deaths were expected to be released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Seeks Quick Deal With Arafat  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators must close  
a deal on a withdrawal from the West Bank or Israel will carry out 
a U.S.-brokered peace accord unilaterally as it sees fit, Israel's 
prime minister said. Ehud Barak is pressing the Palestinians to 
agree to his terms on the Wye River agreement before Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright arrives in the region on Thursday. The 
statement issued yesterday by Barak's office said the Palestinians 
were not providing ``satisfactory answers'' on key issues. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Rise Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The expected launch of big local investment trusts  
sent Japanese stock prices sharply higher today. The Nikkei gained 
319.60 points to close at 17,918.97. 

</P>
<P>
	White Sox 7, Athletics 2  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Carlos Lee drove in four runs and James Baldwin  
won his fifth straight decision yesterday as the Chicago White Sox 
finally solved Kevin Appier and beat the Oakland Athletics 7-2. The 
loss knocked Oakland one game behind Boston in the AL wild-card 
hunt after the Red Sox beat Anaheim 7-4 yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Expos 8, Reds 6  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Geoff Blum's triple drove in the tying and  
go-ahead runs in the sixth inning yesterday as the Montreal Expos 
spoiled Pete Harnisch's second attempt for his 100th career victory 
with an 8-6 win over the Cincinnati Reds. Harnisch, who lost his 
previous start to end a personal eight-game winning streak, had a 
5-0 lead and held Montreal hitless through the first four innings. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
