<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dairy Farmers OK Pricing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dairy farmers have overwhelmingly approved a  
plan by the Agriculture Department to soften regional disparities 
in the way milk is priced, although many producers are looking to 
Congress to rewrite the proposal before it takes effect. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA has not released the results of a referendum on the plan,  
but a senator who has seen them said Monday that it was approved by 
97 percent of the producers who voted nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it would hurt many farmers outside the upper Midwest,  
the plan was expected to be approved because milk prices would 
otherwise be deregulated as of Oct. 1. The vote was conducted Aug. 
2-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reforms are not all that we had hoped, but they push our  
national dairy policy in the right direction,'' said Sen. Herbert 
Kohl, D-Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Galen, a spokesman for the National Milk Producers  
Federation, said ``the referendum was a choice between the lesser 
of two evils. The most egregious evil is having no federal order 
program. ... It's no surprise that dairy producers very grudgingly 
and with a great deal of reservation did vote in the USDA 
proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His group estimated that producers would lose $200 million a  
year under the new system. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current system, guaranteed minimum prices for fluid  
milk are lowest in the upper Midwest and highest in the South and 
West, up to $3 per hundred pounds higher in some places, because 
the price is based on a farm's distance from Eau Claire, Wis. The 
Depression-era system was designed to spur production in areas 
where it had been scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Congress scheduled the system for elimination and  
ordered USDA to come up with a new plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee voted 32-15 earlier this month  
to block the USDA plan and implement an alternative proposal that 
is closer to the current pricing system. The legislation is 
sponsored by more than 220 lawmakers, a majority of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to USDA, the largest dairy cooperative in the  
nation, Dairy Farmers of America, said its members were approving 
the pricing plan reluctantly. ``Our 'yes' vote does not mean that 
dairy farmers can live with the final rule. They cannot! 
Economically, the income and livelihood of many dairy farm families 
will suffer significantly under your proposal,'' the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA officials declined to comment Monday on the referendum. The  
results were to be released officially Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
