<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China OKs Tax on Savings Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's legislature approved a tax on savings  
account interest Monday, trying to boost a slowing economy by 
encouraging consumers to save less and spend more. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax, meant to reduce the incentive to save, adds to a string  
of increasingly desperate economic measures. Slack consumer demand 
has led to a 22-month-long slide in prices that officials are 
afraid could bankrupt Chinese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail sales are largely unchanged despite repeated cuts in  
interest rates and billions of dollars injected into the economy 
through public works projects. Savings rates are among the highest 
in the world at 40 percent of household income. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic growth has slowed considerably, falling to 7.1 percent  
in the second quarter of the year from 8.3 percent in the first 
three months. 
</P>
<P>
	The new tax is to be imposed on both Chinese- and  
foreign-currency accounts, the official Xinhua News Agency said. It 
did not say when the tax would be imposed or give the rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Savings accounts earned about $25 billion in interest last year,  
according to Xinhua. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue from the new tax will be used for unemployment benefits,  
welfare payments and pensions, Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng was 
quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, the legislature approved raising the national debt  
by $7.3 billion through the sale of treasury bonds to fund state 
spending to stimulate growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Half the money will go to the central government and half will  
be lent to local governments, Xinhua said. The money will be spent 
on infrastructure construction, technological innovation and 
environmental protection projects. 
</P>
<P>
	State spending was a key factor in China's strong economic  
growth late last year after the government issued a special $12.1 
billion infrastructure bond and pushed state banks to increase 
their lending by the same amount. 
</P>
<P>
	However, growth in state spending has fallen sharply this year.  
Fixed-asset investment rose by just 3.8 percent year-on-year in 
July, down from 22.7 percent growth in the first quarter of this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is increasing payments to laid-off workers, pay  
for civil servants and export tax rebates as part of its strategy 
to jump-start economic growth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
