<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CD-ROM Can Help With Digital Camera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Digital cameras are becoming commonplace, but that doesn't mean  
getting the right one for your needs is necessarily easy -- or 
cheap. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because selecting a digital camera requires many choices  
on issues most of us don't know exist, let alone understand. If you 
think megapixel is Tinkerbell on steroids and that interpolation is 
a couple of residents shaking hands in Warsaw, Poland, you'll 
probably need a little help in your shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	John Stewart, a mellow-voiced technical audiobook guru from  
Spring Grove, Minn., has a new CD-ROM title that can help. It's 
called ``How To Buy Your First Digital Camera.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart has been doing this sort of thing since 1991, when he  
made his first audiobook, ``The DOS Tape,'' and his efforts since 
have been consistently good, taking complex technology and making 
it understandable. 
</P>
<P>
	``How To Buy Your First Digital Camera'' is divided into five  
chapters that help you assess your needs, grasp basic concepts, 
choose the best camera configuration, review storage options, and 
understand accessories and power sources. He also deals with image 
editors and includes two freeware image editing programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The image editing programs are especially handy, since they  
often can fix whatever composition or lighting mistakes you made 
when you took the digital picture. One of the programs is 
``Irfanview,'' written by Irfan Skiljan, a student at Vienna 
University of Technology in Austria. You can crop and enhance 
images, and add text and special effects. 
</P>
<P>
	The other program is Ultimate Paint from MegaLux, a Hungarian  
company. It's a paint-draw program with some built-in photo 
processing functions. 
</P>
<P>
	The CD-ROM uses whatever Internet browser you have and offers  
you the option of either reading the text or listening to Stewart. 
Both MP3 and Real Audio formats are supported. Other than Windows 
95 or better, the only other requirement is a 24-speed CD-ROM 
drive. (Anything slower and the audio will be a bit choppy, 
although you could work around that by copying the audio files to 
your hard drive.) 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart also wins points by shipping the CD-ROM in a plain  
cardboard mailer. He calls his company Audio Computer Information, 
Inc., and a flier explains the lack of fancy packaging: ``At ACI, 
we think our customers know that using a 'king-sized cereal box'' 
to hold one disk and a sheet of paper is silly. We prefer to leave 
untapped all the natural resources required to make that box.'' 
Amen. 
</P>
<P>
	``How To Buy Your First Digital Camera'' costs $24.95 including  
shipping. It's available at (800) 647-8273. The company's web site 
is www.acpress.com. 
</P>
<P>
	And, for the record, a pixel is a ``picture element,'' one of  
the small ``tiles'' that make up a digital picture. Megapixel 
indicates resolution of 1,280 x 960 pixels or more. Interpolation 
is the process of averaging pixel information when scaling an 
image. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
