<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How JoePa Spent His Summer? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Anybody who knows how Joe Paterno spent his summer should not  
have been surprised by Penn State beating Arizona 41-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Paterno is scary good at his job every weekend, but even better  
with extra time to prepare. Penn State is 19-9-1 in bowl games 
during his tenure, but that mark pales alongside the 28-5 record in 
openers the Nittany Lions carried into Saturday's matchup with the 
Wildcats. 
</P>
<P>
	Making matters worse for Arizona, Paterno was cooped up at home  
for long stretches this summer while his wife, Sue, recuperated 
from a broken hip. After watching Penn State alternate 
quarterbacks, run reverses and open up the offense in ways his 
detractors dared him to, it's obvious JoePa didn't spend his days 
padding back and forth to the refrigerator. 
</P>
<P>
	He was watching film, tearing through sketch pads and plotting  
what to do with last year's backup passer, junior Rashard Casey, 
whose athletic ability intrigued Paterno as much as his 
unpredictability scared him. And at age 73, this old dog proved 
capable of learning some new tricks. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona took its No. 3 ranking to Happy Valley, Pa., expecting a  
great defense and found one -- ``We've volunteered for a dangerous 
mission,'' Wildcat coach Dick Tomey said coming in. ``Most of our 
guys have never been east of Denver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So imagine Tomey's shock when No. 4 Penn State came out Saturday  
playing like one of those pass-happy Pac-10 teams he sees all the 
time on the other side of the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State coach John Cooper doesn't have to imagine.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now I know how Dick Tomey felt yesterday,'' Cooper said after  
his ninth-ranked Buckeyes got beat 23-12 by 12th-ranked Miami. ``I 
feel the same way today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The words ``gambling'' and ``college football'' should be used  
in the same sentence with the great caution, but they belong 
together anytime Top 25 teams agree to play each other before Labor 
Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper, like Tomey, took a big risk, and both took a big fall.  
While Penn State climbed to No. 2 with the win, Arizona slid all 
the way to No. 15. Miami moved up to eighth, while Ohio State 
slipped to No. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	But both losing coaches should be praised more than punished in  
the long run. Paterno admitted he probably wouldn't have taken 
Arizona on in the opener if the game was scheduled for Tucson. And 
Hurricanes coach Butch Davis, in the midst of a rebuilding effort 
to put Miami back in the national championship mix, had precious 
little to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	What both losing coaches will count on now is the short memories  
of poll voters. Last season, Arizona lost a shootout to UCLA late 
in the Pac-10 race, and with it, a shot at the Rose Bowl. Ohio 
State lost to Michigan State the first weekend of November and 
didn't have enough time to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're going to lose, you better lose early,'' Cooper said.  
``Then you better win the rest of your games then hope that you get 
some help from some other teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, whose Seminoles were the No. 1  
preseason pick, got some help from other teams, but not the way he 
planned. His team was scheduled to open against Auburn. But after 
the school fired Bowden's son, Terry, as coach in midseason, Auburn 
paid $500,000 to buy out of a two-year, home-and-home deal with the 
Seminoles rather than face Bowden's wrath. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisiana Tech was a last-minute substitute, but for a while,  
the Bulldogs looked like anything but stand-ins. The score was tied 
at 7-7 late in the half, and it wasn't until Heisman Trophy 
candidate Peter Warrick took off on an electrifying stop-and-go 
20-yard touchdown that the Seminoles took control en route to a 
41-7 win. 
</P>
<P>
	All the maneuvering over the weekend left the two old guys,  
Bowden, 69, and Paterno, perched at the top of what is supposed to 
be a young man's game. Both are in their 33rd season of coaching, 
and while we're used to seeing the two close friends arm-wrestling 
each other for career achievement marks -- bowl victories, most wins 
by active Division I-A coaches -- this could be the year they do it 
face-to-face for a national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, it's early, but you underestimate the fire still burning  
in both men at your own risk. Last month, Penn State's 
All-Everything linebacker LaVar Arrington told Sports Illustrated 
that the magazine was right to rank his team No. 1. ``We're going 
to whip up on some people,'' Arrington said. 
</P>
<P>
	When those words got back to Paterno, he reminded Arrington that  
talking was easy. It's backing it up that's hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's never been part of a national championship team and he  
doesn't know how to get there,'' Paterno said. ``Maybe he needs 
some of the older people who have been there to show him the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
