<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army May Change 'Dated' Ad Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army is wondering whether its ``Be all  
that you can be'' ad campaign might be less than it should be, 
given a falloff in enlistments. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been rated one of the most popular jingles of the century,  
but with a new century approaching, the military's largest branch 
is looking for new ways to fill its depleted ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	The slogan has ``tremendous value because it is recognizable and  
part of the military culture,'' Army Secretary Louis Caldera told 
The Associated Press on Monday. ``The question is whether it is the 
right slogan for today's 18-to-24-year-olds,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's already less prominent in Army ads, coming only as words at  
the end of more fast-paced MTV-style ads rather than as part of the 
storyline, he said. While the Army may retain the slogan, future 
ads may appeal to the patriotic spirit of young people as well as 
the opportunities for self-improvement, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Smith, spokesman for the Army Recruiting Command at Fort  
Knox in Kentucky, said the ad campaign is getting a ``thorough 
relooking.'' Smith stressed that no decision has been made on 
whether the slogan will be kept. 
</P>
<P>
	Abandoning the slogan, introduced in 1981, wouldn't be easy  
because it has been so successfully identified with the Army, Smith 
said. But with this fiscal year's enlistment goal of 74,500 men and 
women expected to fall at least 7,000 short in the worst recruiting 
year since 1979, there's also a recognition it may be time to 
jiggle the jingle. 
</P>
<P>
	Roland Rust, professor of advertising and marketing at  
Vanderbilt University, said the Army slogan rivals Nike's ``Just Do 
It'' for staying power. However, he said, ``You have to ask whether 
Generation-X is wanting to be all that it can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be the case that the current generation is a little  
more pragmatic and short term in its orientation. They are saying, 
'What's in it for me,''' Rust said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Advertising Age magazine ranked ``Be all that  
you can be'' the No. 2 jingle of the century, behind McDonald's 
``You deserve a break today'' and ahead of Pepsi's ``Pepsi Cola 
hits the spot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Garfield, Advertising Age's advertising critic, contended it  
would be a mistake, in these booming economic times, to change the 
core message of that 18-year-old jingle -- that the Army offers a 
way to tap one's inner strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the economy is bad and money is tight, the Army looks  
magnificent, but right now it's not a very good deal unless the 
prospective recruit can see some benefit that doesn't come down to 
dollars and cents,'' Garfield said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was the most effective slogan they had,'' said  
Paul Reuther of Ijamsville, Md., questioned as he was leaving work 
in downtown Washington. ``A friend of mine, ... a pacifist, always 
said it was a great slogan because that's what we all should do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Heather Blackburn, a George Washington University student  
from Sacramento, Calif., thinks the slogan may need a face-lift. A 
22-year-old friend of hers just enlisted in the Army and his 
friends gave him some ribbing about being all he could be. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that contemporary,'' Blackburn said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Army plans to spend at least $92 million on an ad campaign  
aimed at increasing new enlistees next year to 80,000, Smith said. 
Among other stratagems, he said, are sending younger people to work 
in recruiting offices and giving new recruits leave after basic 
training to talk to their friends back home about the Army 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	All the military services are finding it tough to attract young  
people when the economy is good, jobs are plentiful and more high 
school graduates are going on to college. 
</P>
<P>
	But Smith said the Army has ``the largest sales barrier because  
we have the image of people in the mud; we tend to take hits a 
little harder.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
