<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Visit New York State Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- While his wife hugged babies in true  
candidate style, President Clinton today repeated his call for 
using federal budget surpluses to shore up Medicare and Social 
Security instead of offering Americans a tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton visited the  
New York State Fair, and attended a luncheon with State Comptroller 
Carl McCall. Clinton seized the chance to talk about the budget 
surplus, comparing himself and Congress to ``farmers sitting on a 
good crop'' and trying to figure out how to use that crop to their 
best advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a great crop last year. We're sitting on a lot of  
money,'' he said. ``What are we going to do with it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who is considering a run for the Senate from New  
York, hugged babies, signed autographs and accepted gifts of 
flowers and notecards from people in the crowd. Working the rope 
line alongside her was Mike Bragman, majority leader of the New 
York State Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	One woman held up a sign saying, ``Clinton for Senate,'' and  
nearby a man had a T-shirt with an electronic image of himself with 
Mrs. Clinton. The first lady said she is ``learning a lot about the 
diversity of New York'' as she travels the state listening to 
people, and has seen a spirit of unity ``that really does represent 
the best of this state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``New York has always been at the center of whatever is  
happening, not only in our country but in the world,'' Mrs. Clinton 
said. ``But as much progress as we have made, we know we have more 
work to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton offered his memories of state fairs he has attended in  
his political life -- including one in Arkansas, where he wore a 
pinstripe suit and wingtip shoes, and ended up riding a horse. 
</P>
<P>
	The first family shook hands with some of more than 2,500  
cheering well-wishers who greeted them on their arrival at the 
airport here today. 
</P>
<P>
	Officially, Mrs. Clinton is only exploring a run in New York in  
2000, but today's destination was a clue that she intends to go 
ahead with the campaign. The Clintons are spending five days at a 
borrowed estate in Skaneateles in the scenic Finger Lakes region. 
The venue will allow Mrs. Clinton to do a little politicking in a 
heavily Republican part of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's dinner at the estate of film producer Jane Rosenthal  
brought in about $1 million for the Democratic National Committee 
and Mrs. Clinton's expected campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	For $25,000 a couple, attendees heard rock singer Jon Bon Jovi  
and ate lobster salad with organic greens. 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner was the last event in a busy weekend of Democratic  
fund raising in the Hamptons, a swank group of towns on the Long 
Island seashore. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons used the Hamptons home of filmmaker Steven  
Spielberg as a base while attending five Democratic events. Four 
brought in cash for Mrs. Clinton's presumed race, or for Democratic 
candidates generally. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Wolfson, spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory  
committee, said the campaign expected to collect about $400,000 
during the weekend. That is about half the total she expected to 
bring in during the entire vacation trip, which began with 
fund-raisers on the Massachusetts resort islands of Nantucket and 
Martha's Vineyard, and will end with two events near Skaneateles on 
Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
