<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Cleared for Late-Term Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Supreme Court has cleared the way for  
a 14-year-old girl to get a late-term abortion in another state. 
</P>
<P>
	On a 3-2 telephone conference vote Sunday, the high court  
overturned Appeals Court Judge Michael Ryan's decision Saturday to 
bar the girl from having the procedure performed in Kansas, said 
John MacDonald, the Supreme Court's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan's ruling came after Gov. Jane Hull and state Attorney  
General Janet Napolitano argued that the pregnancy may be too 
advanced to terminate. The girl is said to be 24 weeks pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	A ward of the state since she was 5 and now a ward of Maricopa  
County Superior Court, the girl told authorities she was raped. She 
requested an abortion 14 weeks into the pregnancy but then ran 
away, showing up again only recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was brought before the appeals court after Superior  
Court Judge William Sargeant on Saturday reaffirmed an earlier 
decision to permit the abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona Republic newspaper, which reported Ryan's ruling  
Sunday, said it was not clear why the judge decided to overturn the 
decision allowing the abortion to go forward. Rulings related to 
the case have been kept secret because the girl is a juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court's majority on Sunday said Sargeant did not  
``abuse his discretion'' nor was his ruling ``clearly erroneous,'' 
said MacDonald, reading a copy of the court's order. 
</P>
<P>
	No Arizona clinics provide abortions after 20 weeks. Late-term  
abortions in Arizona are allowed only when the life or health of 
the mother is in danger. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately known if the girl was already in Kansas,  
where late-term abortions are allowed in some circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Hull and other state officials declined to comment Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Carolyn Gerster, chairwoman of Arizona Right to Life, said  
she's outraged at the high court's decision, saying by this time, 
the case was really that of a premature baby, not a fetus. ``What 
crime did this baby commit to be sentenced to death?'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bruce Miller, director of Arizona Right to Choose, said the  
Supreme Court made the right decision. and society must respect the 
girl's decision ``and let her get on with her life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
