<HEADLINE> US Open Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three months after she won the last of her 22  
Grand Slam tournament titles, Steffi Graf has disappeared from the 
WTA Tour rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	At No. 3 in the world, he 30-year-old German right-hander became  
the highest-ranked player ever to retire from professional play. 
She informed the WTA Tour on Saturday of her decision to remove 
herself from the rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Smith Court in 1977, Chris Evert in 1990, Manuela  
Maleeva-Fragniere in 1994, Martina Navratilova in 1995 and Kimiko 
Date in 1996 all requested their names be removed from the rankings 
shortly after retiring. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NOW A ROUTINE:* Nicolas Escude of France has raised the  
come-from-behind rally to an art form. 
</P>
<P>
	At the 1998 Australian Open, Escude rallied from two sets down  
to win three consecutive matches, the first time that has been done 
in the open era. En route to the quarterfinals, he defeated Magnus 
Larsson, Richey Reneberg and Nicolas Kiefer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Escude did it again, dropping the first two sets 4-6,  
4-6 to Magnus Gustafsson before winning the next three 7-6 (8-6), 
6-2, 6-4 as the U.S. Open began its two-week run at the National 
Tennis Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Gustafsson had two match points in the third-set tiebreaker.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ATTENDANCE UP:* The WTA Tour is becoming more popular.  
</P>
<P>
	Attendance for the 1999 tour has already surpassed 3 million,  
the first time that many people have watched women's tennis prior 
to the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	With a record crowd of 74,236 at the Pilot Pen tournament in New  
Haven, Conn., last week, the WTA Tour 1999 attendance total is 
3,026,491 in 42 tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	The attendance record of 3,675,094 was set last year.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UNLUCKY LOSER:* Phillip King of Long Beach, Calif., has yet to  
win a match in his two ATP Tour events. But he has a good reason. 
</P>
<P>
	By the luck of the draw, the 17-year-old right-hander had to  
play Pete Sampras, the world's top player and reigning Wimbledon 
champion, in the Mercedes-Benz Cup in Los Angeles in July. Then, 
playing in his first U.S. Open, King's first-round opponent was 
12th-seeded Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands, who won Wimbledon 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	King received a wild-card entry into the U.S. Open by winning  
the USTA National Boys' 18-and-under title in Kalamazoo, Mich. He 
received a wild-card entry into the Mercedes-Benz Cup by winning 
the Boys' 18 title at the Easter Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPECIAL EXHIBIT:* Althea Gibson, Arthur Ashe, Bill Tilden, Don  
Budge, Jimmy Connors and John McEnroe will be among the stars at 
the U.S. Open this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The former champions are part of an exhibit entitled ``Their  
Eyes on the Prize,'' which can be viewed at newly renovated Louis 
Armstrong Stadium at the National Tennis Center, site of the year's 
final Grand Slam tournament. The exhibit is jointly presented by 
the United States Tennis Association and the International Tennis 
Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Historic trophies and champions from more than 100 years of U.S.  
National Championships will be featured in the exhibition, 
including Richard Sears, Helen Wills Moody, Helen Jacobs, Tony 
Trabert, Billie Jean King and Chris Evert. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the Hall of Fame's key missions is to bring tennis  
history to broader audiences and tennis enthusiasts beyond the 
walls of the Hall of Fame Museum in Newport, R.I.,'' said Jane 
Brown, president of the International Tennis Hall of Fame. ``By 
teaming with the USTA to present this exhibition at the U.S. Open, 
we will give more people an opportunity to learn about and 
appreciate the sport's rich history.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ACES FOR DOLLARS:* When Lindsay Davenport, Venus Williams or  
any other player on the WTA Tour serves an ace at this year's U.S. 
Open, they will be scoring points with hundreds of New York City 
girls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chase Manhattan Bank will donate $50 for every ace served  
during women's singles matches at the 1999 U.S. Open to fund the 
Chase Tennis Camps for Girls, a project of the City Parks 
Foundation and City of New York Parks &AMP; Recreation. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase, sponsor of the U.S. Open women's singles, launched the  
Chase Tennis Camps for Girls, the first free citywide program to 
identify and develop the tennis skills of talented young female 
players, in 1997. The 150 girls, 30 from each of the city's five 
boroughs, ages 10-16, will receive a free six-week tennis 
instruction program, with the program culminating with the girls 
being honored at the season-ending Chase Championships at Madison 
Square Garden Nov. 15-21. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
