<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Sets Economic Growth Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government is aiming for 5 percent  
average annual economic growth over the next eight to 10 years, the 
Economics Ministry said in a report released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, carried by the ITAR-Tass news agency, gave no  
details on how the government plans to achieve that somewhat 
optimistic goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's economy has contracted for each of the past 10 years  
with the exception of 1997, when it grew by 0.4 percent. The 
economy is forecast to contract by 2 percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economics Ministry report, which was reviewed during  
Monday's Cabinet meeting, predicts industrial production will grow 
by 4 percent and agriculture by 3 percent in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Production in Russia has risen in the past year, after years of  
decline, because the devaluation of the ruble last August made 
imports prohibitively expensive for most Russians and increased 
demand for cheap domestic goods. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russia's finances remain in sad shape. Its biggest problem  
is paying off its massive foreign debt, which will hit $166 billion 
on January 1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
