<HEADLINE> Texas Dragging Death Trial To Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- The case against the second of three whites  
charged in the dragging death of a black man begins with jury 
selection Tuesday a three hours' drive from the East Texas town 
where the crime took place. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Russell Brewer, 32, is charged with murder in the 1998  
slaying of James Byrd Jr. Brewer could get the death penalty for 
the crime, one of the nation's most grisly racial killings since 
the civil rights era. 
</P>
<P>
	His alleged accomplice John William King was found guilty in  
February in Jasper -- the town the crime occurred -- and sentenced to 
death. A third defendant, Shawn Allen Berry, remains in jail, 
waiting for a trial date. 
</P>
<P>
	State District Judge Monter Lawlis moved Brewer's case 150 miles  
west to this central Texas town after defense attorneys argued that 
the people of Jasper were likely to convict to try to salvage their 
small town's reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection is expected to last at least two weeks, with  
testimony to begin Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd, 49, was chained to a pickup and dragged to pieces along a  
rural road. Prosecutors said King and Brewer meant to use the 
killing to launch a hate group and to initiate Berry into their 
ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	After his arrest, Berry allegedly told police that Brewer  
spray-painted Byrd's face black before the victim was chained to 
the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer has been in and out of prison on drug and burglary  
charges, and prosecutors believe he helped organize a white 
supremacist gang behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's attorney, Doug Barlow, did not return calls for  
comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
