<DOCNO> APW19990830.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 17:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Named in Free Speech Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush was accused in a  
lawsuit filed Monday of violating the free speech rights of 
protesters. His lawyers, meanwhile, persuaded a judge to quash a 
subpoena in another legal matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists allege that the Republican presidential  
front-runner has given state troopers ``unbridled discretion'' to 
target protesters picketing on a public sidewalk in front of the 
Governor's Mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Texas Constitution does not stop at the sidewalk in front  
of the Governor's Mansion,'' said Rick Abraham, executive director 
of Texans United, one of the environmental groups suing Bush. 
Abraham said he was arrested twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's office contends the protesters were arrested because they  
failed to remain within the area set aside for demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision regarding protesters was made by the Department  
of Public Safety to protect the safety of pedestrians and 
protesters around the governor's mansion,'' said Bush spokesman Ray 
Sullivan. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were concerned that protesters blocking sidewalks could  
result in people walking in the street or otherwise jeopardizing 
their safety,'' Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other case, District Judge John Dietz quashed a subpoena  
seeking Bush's testimony in a whistleblower case filed by a former 
head of the Texas Funeral Service Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General John Cornyn had argued that Bush should not be  
forced to testify. ``This is not a search for the truth. This is 
about harassment. This is about politics,'' he told the judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Eliza May alleges that she was fired as head of the funeral  
commission over an investigation of Service Corp. International, a 
Houston-based funeral company that had given campaign contributions 
to Bush. Her lawyers want to question Bush about the investigation, 
which resulted in recommended fines of $445,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The company denies wrongdoing and says the commission  
misinterpreted state embalming law. It is contesting the fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornyn said the state government is sued 10 times a day, and if  
the governor were forced to testify in each one he would have no 
time for anything else. 
</P>
<P>
	``This ruling is an important one for Governor Bush and for  
future governors because it essentially says that the governor 
should not be used to generate publicity for lawsuits in which he 
is not involved,'' spokesman Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Herring, representing Ms. May, said Bush ``is not ...  
simply an uninvolved third party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor is alleged here ... as a co-conspirator in this  
matter, in this very case,'' he said. ``That means he and he alone 
could have personal knowledge of the elements of the conspiracy 
that we need to ask about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would push forward with the case and question others,  
including the governor's chief of staff and his general counsel. 
``Obviously, this is not about getting Governor Bush,'' he said. 
``This is a a whistleblower lawsuit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Cornyn, ``We finally got some relief from the kind of  
innuendo and rumor and speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants in the case are the funeral commission, SCI and  
Robert Waltrip, the company's founder and chairman, who is a 
longtime Bush supporter. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May, a former Democratic Party treasurer, alleges that SCI,  
whose political action committee gave Bush $35,000 in 1996 and 
1997, worked with Bush's staff to interfere with an investigation 
of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	She has asked the court to find Bush in contempt for filing what  
she calls a false affidavit in his attempt to block a subpoena. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said in his July 20 affidavit, ``I have had no  
conversations with SCI officials, agents, or representatives 
concerning the investigation or any dispute arising from it.'' He 
also said he had no personal knowledge of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed on behalf of the environmentalists seeks to  
force the state to acknowledge the demonstrators' right to protest 
in front of the Governor's Mansion. It was filled by Texans United, 
Downwinders At Risk and three demonstrators against Bush, the 
Department of Public Safety and the three DPS commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of about 20 demonstrators paced the sidewalk in front of  
the mansion Monday afternoon without incident. It was the same area 
where demonstrators had been arrested on four previous occasion -- 
March 11, March 29, April 19 and May 25. In each case, charges of 
blocking an entry way were dropped by the Travis County's district 
attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is clear about this pattern of arrests is that it was  
designed to intimidate and harass protesters, not to keep the 
sidewalks clear of pedestrians,'' said David Kahne, an attorney 
with the American Civil Liberties Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Abraham, one of the plaintiffs, contended that the arrests  
started after Bush decided to run for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Vinger, DPS spokesman, declined comment on the lawsuit, but  
said there is no written policy on how state police should deal 
with protesters. He said protests are considered on a case-by-case 
basis. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Michael Holmes contributed to this story.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 12:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Seahawks' Fritz Shurmur Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Seattle Seahawks defensive coordinator  
Fritz Shurmur, the architect of the Green Bay Packers' defense that 
dominated the league in 1996, died today at age 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was in his 20th year as an NFL defensive coordinator. He  
followed Mike Holmgren to Seattle in January when Holmgren was 
hired as the Seahawks' coach and GM. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to the Green Bay area for treatment of esophageal  
and liver cancer, which was found during a routine checkup in May. 
Shurmur died at his home in nearby Suamico. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur's death was first reported today by The Post-Crescent of  
Appleton and confirmed by a team source who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur spent five seasons with the Packers and was instrumental  
in the team's run to consecutive Super Bowl appearances. He also 
served as a defensive coach with the Phoenix Cardinals, the Los 
Angeles Rams, the New England Patriots and the Detroit Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur joined the Packers in 1994, replacing current Green Bay  
head coach Ray Rhodes as defensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was the league's longest-serving defensive coordinator.  
He was the Rams' defensive coordinator from 1983-90 and spent three 
years in Phoenix before joining the Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was known as a defensive innovator and a premiere  
teacher of the game. He wrote four books on defense and coached for 
his entire adult life, beginning in 1954 as a graduate assistant at 
his alma mater, Albion (Mich.) College. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a defensive coach at the University of Wyoming from  
1962-70 and head coach at the school from 1971-74. A native of 
Wyandotte, Mich., he held a master's degree in education and 
received an honorary doctorate from Albion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren had assigned Shurmur's duties in Seattle to linebackers  
coach Jim Lind, who received Shurmur's endorsement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 12:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Seahawks' Fritz Shurmur Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Seattle Seahawks defensive coordinator  
Fritz Shurmur, the architect of the Green Bay Packers' defense that 
dominated the league in 1996, died today at age 67. 
</P>
