</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was the league's longest-serving defensive coordinator.  
He was the Rams' defensive coordinator from 1983-90 and spent three 
years in Phoenix before joining the Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was known as a defensive innovator and a premiere  
teacher of the game. He wrote four books on defense and coached for 
his entire adult life, beginning in 1954 as a graduate assistant at 
his alma mater, Albion (Mich.) College. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a defensive coach at the University of Wyoming from  
1962-70 and head coach at the school from 1971-74. A native of 
Wyandotte, Mich., he held a master's degree in education and 
received an honorary doctorate from Albion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren had assigned Shurmur's duties in Seattle to linebackers  
coach Jim Lind, who received Shurmur's endorsement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 09:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Corn Up; Wheat Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and corn futures prices were up slightly  
or unchanged in early dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade, while 
wheat futures fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices, which ended on a high note Friday, got continued  
support from forecasts for dry weather in much of the Midwest 
growing region through the weekend, which could result in smaller 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say corn prices should stay fairly steady as traders  
await crop estimates from the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Crops 
will be harvested in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say wheat prices were getting pressure from low export  
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	In early dealings today, wheat for December delivery fell a cent  
to $2.78 1/2 a bushel; December corn rose a cent to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats were unchanged at $1.14 a bushel; November soybeans 
also broke even at $4.70 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock and meet futures prices were mostly lower in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .12 cent to 66.67 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle were up .08 cent to 79 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell .32 cent to 44.65 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies fell .35 cents to 58.30 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
