<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Cuts Long-Distance Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. is cutting prices for long-distance  
phone calls to 7 cents a minute and simplifying rates in response 
to a price war that is hurting the company's revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate is still higher than offers introduced early this month  
from MCI WorldCom and Sprint. But AT&AMP;T hopes its easy-to-use plan 
will stem customer defections. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing how complicated this industry can make saying,  
'Hello,''' AT&AMP;T chairman Mike Armstrong said in a teleconference 
call this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The new AT&AMP;T rate announced today is good for calls made any  
time. Customers who want the rate also must pay the company a fee 
of $5.95 a month. AT&AMP;T had charged 15 cents a minute around the 
clock with no monthly fee or 10 cents a minute with a $4.95 fee. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, MCI offers weekend and weekday nighttime rates of  
5 cents a minute, but daytime fees go up to 25 cents a minute. Its 
monthly fee, though, is $1.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint charges 5 cents per minute for nighttime calls for $5.95  
a month, with rates going up to 10 cents a minute for other calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The price wars are causing a larger-than-expected revenue  
erosion in AT&AMP;T's long-distance business. But AT&AMP;T said its 
financial results this year should nevertheless meet the 
expectations of Wall Street analysts due to surprising strong 
growth in its wireless and other promising businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, AT&AMP;T's revenue is expected to grow between 5 percent  
and 7 percent, with per-share profits between $2.13 and $2.20. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
