<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. Must Disclose Pension Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Employees considering retirement have the  
right to know that their company is seriously thinking of benefit 
changes that might affect their decision, a federal appeals court 
ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	In a pair of 2-1 rulings Monday, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals said an employer's duty to keep employees informed of their 
retirement options includes not only answering questions truthfully 
but also disclosing information without being asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Other appellate courts have required employers to disclose, when  
asked, that they were ``seriously considering'' new retirement 
packages. Serious consideration has been defined to cover 
discussion by senior management with the authority to implement 
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's rulings reinstated suits by an Exxon employee and six  
Pacific Bell employees who said they would have delayed retirement 
if they'd been told the company was considering a sweetened 
retirement package. Their suits seek participation in the deals 
that were offered later. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal judges had dismissed both suits, saying the companies  
hadn't lied and had no duty to volunteer the information. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court said a pension plan, which has the duty to  
protect its members' interests, must notify them of potential 
changes, rather than ``penalizing a person who fails to ask the 
right questions at the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's an important step, because ``if you don't know what's  
going on, how do you know to ask a question?'' said Thomas 
Moukawsher, lawyer for the former Exxon employee. He said his 
client, who worked on an oil drilling rig off the Southern 
California coast, was ``completely reliant on the chain of 
communications that the company had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Severson, lawyer for Exxon Co. U.S.A., said the ruling  
would create ``fertile ground for lawyers and litigants'' and 
confusion for employers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Exxon employee, Ernest Bins, planned to retire Jan. 1, 1996  
and heard rumors the company was planning to add a cash payment to 
its normal pension. He delayed his retirement date for a month and 
questioned several supervisors through late December but was told 
they knew nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Exxon U.S.A. had been studying the benefit increase as  
an incentive to early retirement for several months, the court 
said. The company president reviewed the proposal in mid-December, 
top executives of the parent Exxon Corp. reviewed and approved it 
in January, and it was formally announced less than two weeks after 
Bins retired. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit would have been worth $35,000 or $40,000 to Bins,  
his lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Bell suit was filed by six employees who took early  
retirement in June 1995 after being told by managers that the 
company was in bad shape, planned layoffs and did not intend to 
make a better offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company actually had a healthy pension plan and was planning  
to offer an improved retirement plan to its union, the court said. 
The plan, adopted in August 1995, would have been worth between 
$27,000 and $99,000 to the six plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In reinstating both suits, the court said both employers had  
seriously considered the improvements before the employees retired, 
and should have disclosed them, with no guarantees. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are Bins vs. Exxon, 98-55662, and Wayne vs. Pacific  
Bell, 97-56456. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
