<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial May Solve Mysterious Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PERU, Ind. (AP) -- Prospective jurors were questioned today as  
the trial of a former nurse accused of killing seven hospital 
patients finally got under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Orville Lynn Majors Jr. arrived this morning at the Miami County  
Courthouse to face the people who will decide his guilt or 
innocence. Prosecutors allege Majors, 37, gave lethal injections to 
dozens of patients at Vermillion County Hospital five years ago, 
but they charged him with just seven murders. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual move to circumvent the effects of pretrial  
publicity, the trial was moved from Vermillion County to nearby 
Clay County, and the jurors were being selected in Miami County, 
more than 100 miles to the northeast. Jurors will be bused each 
week to Clay County, returning to their homes in and around Peru 
for the weekends. 
</P>
<P>
	The first batch of six men and six women, from a pool of 100  
whittled down from hundreds who filled out a questionnaire, were 
questioned this morning. They all said they felt they could serve 
in a trial that could last three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take a lot of time and cost a lot of money for  
me, but if that's what it takes it doesn't really concern me,'' 
said a man identified only as Juror No. 44. 
</P>
<P>
	After both sides questioned a dozen prospects this morning, two  
men and one woman were tentatively chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	By Friday, if the selection proceeds goes as planned, the judge  
and attorneys will have settled on 12 jurors, six alternate jurors 
and four extra jurors who can hear the trial. Special Judge Ernest 
Yelton wants to start the trial Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors suspect Majors in dozens of patients' deaths, but  
they whittled the charges to seven cases they believe exhibit the 
strongest evidence that Majors gave his patients unauthorized and 
lethal injections. 
</P>
<P>
	In Vermillion County Hospital's four-bed intensive care unit,  
120 people died in 1994. But in each of the previous four years, no 
more than 31 ICU patients died. A consultant who studied patient 
charts and nurses' time cards found patients were 43 times more 
likely to die when Majors was on duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Yelton barred prosecutors from using such data at trial, saying  
the state should stick to specific evidence of the seven murders. 
Prosecutors said the state can prove its case without the 
statistical studies. 
</P>
<P>
	In court documents, some relatives say they saw Majors give  
their loved ones shots before they died. Police say vials 
containing traces of the potassium chloride or epinephrine and 
syringes were found at Majors' home and in his van. 
</P>
<P>
	Majors says he's innocent of all charges. Defense lawyer I.  
Marshall Pinkus says jurors won't find it unusual that nurses give 
patients shots or that sick, elderly patients die in intensive care 
units. Some patients and co-workers at the hospital considered 
Majors a hardworking and sympathetic nurse, Pinkus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinting at what is a largely circumstantial case, a deputy  
prosecutor, Nina Alexander, asked several potential jurors today 
whether they needed direct evidence before they could convict 
someone of murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``What if you got up in the morning and there was 2 feet of snow  
on the ground, what would you conclude?'' Alexander asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, it snowed,'' replied Juror No. 543.  
</P>
<P>
	``Did you see it snow?'' Alexander asked. When the juror said,  
``No,'' the prosecutor smiled and replied, ``That's what 
circumstantial evidence is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
