<HEADLINE> Fires Char 200,000 Acres Out West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wind-driven wildfires burned untamed Monday in six Western  
states, crackling across more than 100,000 acres of timber, dry 
brush and cactus, destroying homes and forcing thousands of 
residents to flee. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen fires burned in Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Utah,  
Washington and California, where homes were among 30 structures 
incinerated by a wildfire in Apple Valley some 80 miles northeast 
of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't known how many homes were destroyed, U.S. Forest  
Service spokeswoman Karen McKinley said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 residents left homes Sunday afternoon as 30 mph  
winds pushed flames through 17,000 acres of brush and spiny Joshua 
Trees. Five people were arrested for allegedly looting abandoned 
homes, sheriff's spokeswoman Jennie Risley said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sullivan left the Apple Valley High School evacuation  
center early Monday expecting to find his home in rubble. It was 
still standing. 
</P>
<P>
	Grinning during a cellular telephone call to his wife, he said,  
``Good news. The house is standing. Nothing got burned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty miles to the west, more than 1,200 acres was burning in a  
rugged, brushy area of the Angeles National Forest. More than 4,000 
people, most of them campers, were forced out of San Gabriel 
Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 firefighters battled the blaze with the help of two  
water-dropping helicopters. Desperately needed air tankers were 
unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very seriously hurting with a lack of resources,'' U.S.  
Forest Service spokeswoman Linda Steinberg said. ``We're really 
struggling with it. The San Bernardino fire is taking about 
everything. They take precedence over us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho, said  
100,000 acres were burning in six states on Monday and 10,000 
firefighters were fighting flames. More than 100 aircraft were 
assigned to the fires. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighting ranks were thinning, but James Stone at the Boise  
center said, ``We haven't run out yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The West's largest blaze, a 45,000-acre fire north of Reno, was  
surrounded late Sunday and firefighters were dousing hot spots on 
Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
