<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Describe 'Crisis' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinians described a ``crisis'' atmosphere  
in negotiations with Israel today, just days before Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright's arrival in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was threatening to implement  
the U.S.-brokered Wye agreement according to his interpretation if 
the Palestinians do not back down on two key issues by Thursday: a 
timetable for a West Bank withdrawal and the release of 
Palestinians jailed for anti-Israel activity. Barak had originally 
set a deadline for this evening, but later said he was willing to 
wait a little longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a crisis in the negotiations, and the first reason is  
that of political prisoners,'' Nabil Amr, an aide to Palestinian 
leader Yasser Arafat, told The Associated Press. ``The way Israel 
is dealing with this issue is causing us great worry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A senior adviser to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Osama  
el-Baz, was unable to mediate a breakthrough in separate talks 
Sunday and early today with Arafat and Barak. 
</P>
<P>
	The Egyptians are hoping to oversee a signing ceremony on a  
possible agreement during Albright's visit to the region. 
</P>
<P>
	A Palestinian negotiator, asking not to be identified, said the  
Israelis had made some concessions on prisoners today, but there 
were still gaps. Barak's office indicated Sunday that Israel might 
release Palestinians who had been involved in anti-Israel attacks 
but were members of groups supporting the peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of the prisoners, who enjoy huge support among  
Palestinians, demonstrated in the West Bank town of Nablus to 
pressure the negotiators not to cave in to Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	``No peace and no safety without the release of prisoners,'' one  
woman chanted into a megaphone. 
</P>
<P>
	If Islamic militants held by the Palestinian Authority are  
mistreated, their colleagues will carry out attacks in Israel, said 
a fax signed by the Islamic Jihad and sent today to news agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	It was impossible to immediately confirm the authenticity of the  
fax. 
</P>
<P>
	Top Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and his Israeli  
counterpart, Gilead Sher, were due to resume talks this evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak said Israel was still awaiting ``satisfactory answers''  
from the Palestinians regarding an Israeli plan to time the final 
Wye-mandated withdrawal for February 2000, to coincide with 
achieving a framework for the final phase of the peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians want Wye completed before the year is out, and  
would prefer further West Bank concessions -- Wye will leave them 
with under half of the disputed territory -- before proceeding to 
final status talks. 
</P>
<P>
	After briefing parliament's Defense and Foreign Affairs  
Committee on the talks, Barak said the Palestinians had ``two or 
three'' days to come up with ``satisfactory answers'' to Israeli 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Palestinians do not choose this, we will implement the  
Wye accords as they were signed, as they were written,'' Barak 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	That would mean an open-ended pullout from the West Bank and  
Israel releasing prisoners solely according to its criteria -- 
prospects likely to infuriate the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Erekat said that such ultimatums were counterproductive. He  
rejected Israeli claims that Palestinians were resisting signing 
because they wanted to prompt deeper American involvement in the 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is no agreement by the time Albright arrives, ``we're  
the vulnerable side, the pressure will be put on us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite talks of crisis and ultimatums, each side maintained a  
friendly, optimistic tone: Erekat complimented his Israeli partners 
as ``the toughest negotiators I have seen in the last three 
years.'' Barak said the process was one of ``renewing confidence'' 
after the rancor of the Netanyahu years, and that he still expected 
an agreement by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wye provides for an Israeli withdrawal from at least 11 percent  
of the West Bank. The sides have reached an agreement on opening 
``safe passages'' for Palestinian travel between the Gaza Strip and 
West Bank and the opening of a Palestinian port. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
