<DOCNO> APW19990830.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 08:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canandaigua Brands Founder Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANANDAIGUA, N.Y. (AP) -- Marvin Sands, who developed a bulk wine  
company into the nation's second-largest supplier of wine, died of 
cancer at his home Saturday. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Canandaigua Brands Inc., based in the Rochester suburb of  
Fairport, makes and distributes more than 150 brands of wine, beer 
and spirits. It is second in size only to E&AMP;J Gallo. 
</P>
<P>
	Sands, the son of a wine bottler, graduated from the University  
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. He served as an ensign in the 
U.S. Navy during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1945, Sands took over the operation of a bulk wine supplier  
in Canandaigua that had been purchased by his father. That business 
took off in 1954 when he introduced a successful sweet wine called 
Richard's Wild Irish Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the beginning of today's Canandaigua Brands,'' said  
his son, Richard Sands, after whom the wine was named. ``He 
realized how difficult it is to sell bulk wine. If you charge a 
penny more than the competition, no one wanted to buy. He felt he 
had no ownership. The way to accomplish that was to have a special 
blend and a proprietary name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Wild Irish Rose is only a small part of Canandaigua  
Brands today, it is the best-selling dessert wine in the country, 
Richard Sands said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Canandaigua bought Tenner Bros. Winery in South  
Carolina and the Hammondsport Wine Co., gaining entry into the 
sparkling wine market. 
</P>
<P>
	His acquisitions included Bisceglia Brothers in California,  
Manischewitz Kosher Wines and Widmer Wines. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Sands took over as president of Canandaigua in 1993 and  
became chief executive officer in 1996. Another son, Robert Sands, 
is chief executive officer of international operations, vice 
president and general counsel of Canandaigua Brands and chief 
executive officer of Canandaigua Wine Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his sons, Sands is survived by his wife of 52  
years, Mickey Sands, of Canandaigua; a son-in-law, Dr. Andrew 
Stern, of Pittsford; and several grandchildren. His daughter, Dr. 
Laurie Sands, died of cancer in 1995. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
