<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Mr. Irrelevant' Among Bears Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Jim Finn, ``Mr. Irrelevant'' in this  
year's draft, was among 15 players released Monday by the Chicago 
Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	Finn, a fullback from Pennsylvania, was the last player chosen  
in the draft. That player is honored every June at ``Irrelevant 
Week'' in Newport Beach, Calif. Finn still could end up on the 
five-player practice squad, which will be set Sept. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Moses Moreno, who started one game for the Chicago Bears as a  
rookie last season, was also cut. While the other moves were made 
in the morning, Moreno's release wasn't announced until later that 
evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreno, picked in the seventh round out of Colorado State last  
year, was the No. 3 quarterback for most of the season. But with 
Erik Kramer hurt, Steve Stenstrom ineffective and the Bears' 
offense uninspired, Moreno got his first start against Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	He completed 18-of-41 attempts for 153 yards and one touchdown  
in the 31-17 loss. But he sprained his right ankle on the last 
offensive play of the game and was placed on injured reserve 2 1/2 
weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a victim of numbers this year. With rookie Cade McNown  
and veterans Shane Matthews and Jim Miller, Moreno didn't get much 
playing time. He was 11-of-18 for 108 yards with one interception 
in the preseason. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
