<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American, Pilots Negotiate Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines and its pilots were  
making a last ditch effort Monday to reach an agreement over the 
airline's plans to integrate Reno Air Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Since American's parent company, AMR Corp., announced the Reno  
purchase last December, the two sides have disagreed over how the 
pilots will be merged into the company. The dispute evolved into a 
pilot sickout in February that stranded hundreds of thousands of 
passengers all over the world and cost the company $225 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Allied Pilots Association and the Fort Worth, Texas-based  
company have continued to negotiate since the illegal job action, 
though have been able to reach a solution. The integration of the 
Reno pilots is scheduled to take place Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the sticking points in this deal has been the protocol  
for any future acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to conclude deals with two other unions  
relatively quickly, but after more than nine months of negotiation 
and mediation we are still without an agreement with APA,'' Robert 
Baker, executive vice president of operations, wrote to the 
company's 9,500 pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides agreed to give merger discussions a final attempt  
before American moves ahead with bringing Reno into its system, 
company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	American's plan will bring former Reno pilots into the company  
at the bottom of the seniority list. That means lower-paid Reno 
pilots will get a boost in their salaries, but they will have less 
say in their flying schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, a dozen American pilots who underwent training in July  
will move into captain jobs formerly held by their Reno 
counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the union has been reminding the pilots that they  
must not repeat the February sickout. That illegal job action 
resulted in a federal judge holding the union in contempt when his 
order to return to work was ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	During talks with the judge, the APA agreed to a permanent  
injunction barring the union and its members from any future 
actions -- strike, sickout or slowdown. That decision leaves the 
union with no recourse but to ultimately accept American's decision 
to go forward with integration, according to observers. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has e-mailed its members that U.S. District Judge Joe  
Kendall's order remains in effect and that the APA must comply. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also ordered the pilots' union to pay a $45 million  
judgment as punishment for the sickout. The union has promised an 
appeal of the massive award, which is larger than the union's net 
worth. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
