<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Union Rejects Extra Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Detroit teachers' union today rejected an  
extension of talks proposed by its own negotiators and said 
teachers would not work without a new contract. Classes had been 
scheduled to begin Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The word ``strike'' wasn't used. But when asked if that meant  
the teachers were going on strike, union vice president John Butler 
replied, ``That's another word for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Adamany, the district's interim CEO, said that he was  
disappointed by the vote. He said the 172,000-student district 
would wait until it sees how many teachers report Tuesday before 
deciding whether to hold classes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping teachers will come back to school. But we are not  
at this time encouraging students to come to school until we know 
there are teachers there to teach them,'' Adamany said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this morning, Detroit Public Schools officials and union  
negotiators had agreed to extend their current contract by 10 days 
while they continue to negotiate a new deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a vote later this morning, the Detroit Federation of  
Teachers rejected the extension proposal. After the vote, which was 
held at Cobo Center, teachers headed to the Schools' Center 
Building to picket. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked for them to follow my recommendations to go  
back to work for 10 days while I negotiate. That was my 
recommendation,'' union president John Elliot said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union, unhappy with contract negotiations for the past  
month, had threatened a possible strike before the scheduled start 
of classes. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has not walked out since 1992. A state law passed in  
1994 restricts strikes by public school workers and provides for 
fines equal to a day's pay for each day of the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Anita Griggs, 40, who has been an elementary school teacher for  
15 years, said she wasn't in favor of the contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once they get us in the classrooms, there's no reason to  
bargain in good faith. They've got the labor,'' Ms. Griggs said on 
her way to the union meeting to discuss the negotiations this 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement before the vote, Adamany said a tentative  
agreement on a broad array of issues had been reached, though a few 
issues remained on the table. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
