<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Stamp Will Honor Computer Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- A new postage stamp that celebrates the  
computer chip and its impact on society will be unveiled Wednesday 
at a Maine plant that played a pioneering role in the electronics 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the eight men who were instrumental in the founding of  
Fairchild Semiconductor at the dawn of the computer age will attend 
the ceremony at the South Portland plant that designed and produced 
the chip, or integrated circuit, featured on the stamp. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, which opened in 1962, is the world's oldest  
continuously operating plant for the fabrication of integrated 
circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The computer chip image will appear on one of 15 stamps that  
depict various subjects from the 1960s. The stamps, mounted on a 
decorative sheet, go on sale Sept. 18. Each decade is being 
celebrated by 15-stamp sheets through the Postal Service's 
Celebrate the Century program. Subjects have been selected by a 
national ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just incredibly honored to have the integrated circuit  
and a Fairchild design selected as one of the top science and 
technology developments of the decade, with the others being man 
walking on the moon and the laser,'' said Fran Harrison, director 
of corporate communications for Fairchild. 
</P>
<P>
	Most stamp unveilings take place in Washington, but the close  
link between Fairchild and the subject of the stamp persuaded the 
Postal Service to hold the ceremony in South Portland, said Robert 
Groff, a spokesman for the Postal Service. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of stamp images aren't that specific to a company,''  
Groff said. ``It's pretty rare and kind of special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The eight men who played key roles in the founding of Fairchild  
in Palo Alto. Calif., defected from Shockley Labs in 1957 and set 
out to develop products for the Department of Defense. Known in the 
industry as the ``traitorous eight,'' they developed a process for 
mass-producing silicon transistors. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1959, Robert Noyce and other group members developed a  
transistor that was able to put several functions on one plane, 
leading to the development of an integrated-circuit industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Portland plant was opened three years later,  
participating in the development and fabrication of integrated 
circuits such as the one pictured on the new stamp. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Fairchild's original group members, Gordon Moore and  
Noyce, left Fairchild in 1968 to open a company named Intel. Noyce, 
who died in 1990, was married at the time to Elizabeth Noyce, the 
late Maine philanthropist who moved to Bremen after the couple 
divorced in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Fairchild eventually was purchased by Schlumberger Ltd. and  
later by National Semiconductor, which eliminated the Fairchild 
name in 1989. Eight years later, the company re-emerged as an 
independent entity with its original name. 
</P>
<P>
	Fairchild now employs 8,000 people worldwide, including 1,500 in  
Maine. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
