<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Urged on Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Jewish group is demanding that Hillary Rodham  
Clinton take a stand on the explosive issue of whether to free 
Jonathan Pollard, a former Navy intelligence analyst serving life 
as an Israeli spy. 
</P>
<P>
	While the president and first lady attended fund-raisers in the  
Hamptons on Sunday, Assemblyman Dov Hikind, D-Brooklyn, told a 
sidewalk rally the Pollard case is ``certain to become a serious 
issue in the New York Senate contest.'' Mrs. Clinton is weighing 
whether to run for the seat being vacated by Democrat Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	Hikind said Mrs. Clinton should try to persuade her husband to  
grant clemency for Pollard, who has served 14 years in federal 
prison for leaking U.S. military secrets to Israel in the early 
1980s. The Justice Department has rejected previous demands for his 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleading with Hillary to impress her husband with the  
humanitarian aspects of a pardon for Jonathan Pollard,'' Hikind 
said. ``Hillary has a lot of work to do in our community, and we 
are watching very carefully. She is for the unity of Jerusalem -- 
very nice. But words alone do simply not work. Action is what will 
count, and I am determined to make this the No. 1 issue in our 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hikind said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is expected to oppose  
Mrs. Clinton in next year's Senate race, supports freedom for 
Pollard. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter dated Aug. 9, Hikind asked the first lady to  
intervene. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Mrs. Clinton, declined to  
comment on the letter or Sunday's rally. 
  	   	
</P>
