<HEADLINE> Riley Tours Southern Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- When it comes to education, the South  
is on the rise, Education Secretary Richard W. Riley said Monday as 
he began a five-day, five-state bus trip to visit schools in the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	``The South has made enormous strides in education and we have  
economic prosperity to show for it,'' Riley told a cheering crowd 
gathered at the airport here. The nation's top education 
policy-maker was greeted by Chattanooga Mayor Jon Kinsey and the 
100-member Ooltewah High School band. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley, whose first-time bus tour includes a stop in South  
Carolina, where he once was governor, said the South has emerged as 
a national trendsetter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many more children are in Head Start. More high school  
students are taking the core curriculum to get ready for college. 
And the South has led the nation in reducing the high school 
dropout rate,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before boarding a large charter coach decorated in yellow to  
resemble a school bus, Riley gave a glimpse of a greater picture, 
saying: ``While my tour has a regional flavor, let's also recognize 
we Americans are about to make some important decisions about our 
nation's future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If ever there was a time to be investing in the future, that  
time is now,'' he said, touting Clinton administration initiatives 
to go before Congress this fall. ``This is why we should use our 
nation's budget surplus to protect Social Security, shore up 
Medicare ... and invest in quality education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He praised a new generation of Southern governors for what he  
called ``pro-education agendas.'' Other Southern governors will 
greet Riley along the way as he visits their schools, some of which 
are running well and others the state has had to take over. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the secretary is going to see in the five states is that  
it's not just where you are, it's where you're going,'' said Mark 
Musick, president of the Southern Regional Education Board, an 
advisory panel to Southern governors in 16 states including the 
ones Riley will visit -- Alabama, Georgia, Tennessee and North and 
South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to sense in these stops some feeling that we're  
making progress, that there's some determination about the 
direction we're moving in,'' Musick said in a telephone interview 
Monday. He will meet the tour later this week in Georgia, where his 
organization is based. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
