<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Thurmond Released After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Strom Thurmond was released from the  
hospital Monday after successful surgery for an enlarged prostate. 
</P>
<P>
	The 96-year-old senator, wearing a business suit, walked out  
Walter Reed Army Medical Center accompanied by his wife, Nancy, and 
daughter Julie. 
</P>
<P>
	His spokesman, John DeCrosta, said Thurmond was in good spirits.  
``He's going back to his home (in Alexandria, Va.), and I don't 
anticipate that he'll swing by the office today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina Republican collapsed at a University of South  
Carolina reception while on congressional recess Aug. 20. He was 
briefly admitted to a hospital in Columbia, S.C., and then 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	He was admitted to Walter Reed two days later complaining of  
fatigue and underwent prostate surgery last Wednesday. The 
procedure was originally scheduled for November. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurmond, the oldest and longest serving senator, spent just  
over a week in Walter Reed's Ward 72, where members of Congress and 
senior military officials are often treated. 
</P>
<P>
	As he left the hospital, Thurmond told reporters he was grateful  
for the support and kindness of his many well-wishers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
