<DOCNO> APW19990830.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 07:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dennis Batters N.C. Coastline  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C. (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis stood off North  
Carolina early today and battered the coastline with torrential 
rains and 80 mph winds, leaving tens of thousands of people without 
power. While a hurricane warning was posted for the entire North 
Carolina coast, the Wilmington area bore the early brunt of the 
storm before bands of heavy rain moved north to the Atlantic Beach 
area. Rain fell at a rate of nearly 3 inches an hour, according to 
National Weather Service. Forecasters expected Dennis to turn 
northeast and skirt the coast today but said it could still cause 
serious problems. At 9 a.m. EDT, Dennis was centered about 85 miles 
south of Cape Lookout, N.C. 

</P>
<P>
	US Envoy Asks for Kosovo Cooperation  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- New U.N. ambassador Richard  
Holbrooke appealed again today to the Kosovo population for 
cooperation, saying Serbs and Albanians alike must work toward a 
pluralistic and democratic society. Holbrooke said easing ethnic 
tensions in Yugoslav province is the ultimate test for the United 
Nations. His statement implied that ethnic Albanian revenge attacks 
against the dwindling Serb population in Kosovo must stop. Ethnic 
Albanians, who have a majority in Kosovo, have been seeking to 
avenge the 18-month Serb crackdown that left about 10,000 people 
dead and hundreds of thousands temporary refugees. 

</P>
<P>
	Prevention Said Key in Handling HIV  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With life-prolonging drugs proving to be  
successful in reducing the number of AIDS-related deaths, more 
efforts to control the epidemic should be directed toward 
prevention, health officials say. More than 2,000 scientists, 
doctors, researchers and advocates are in Atlanta this week for the 
National HIV Prevention Conference -- the first national conference 
addressing efforts to monitor and prevent the spread of HIV, the 
virus that causes AIDS. The latest national data on trends in HIV 
infections and AIDS deaths were expected to be released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Nobel Prize Winner Hospitalized  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Nobel Peace Prize winner John Hume was  
recovering today after undergoing emergency surgery for a ruptured 
intestine, the Austria Press Agency reported. The 62-year-old 
helped found the moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party, 
Northern Ireland's leading Catholic party, in 1970. He shared the 
1998 Nobel Peace Prize with Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble. 

</P>
<P>
	Teen Cleared for Late-Term Abortion  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Supreme Court has cleared the way for  
a 14-year-old girl to get a late-term abortion in another state. 
The high court overturned an appeals court decision to bar the girl 
from having the procedure performed in Kansas. The girl is said to 
be 24 weeks pregnant. She told authorities she was raped and 
requested an abortion 14 weeks into the pregnancy but then ran 
away, showing up again only recently. No Arizona clinics provide 
abortions after 20 weeks. Late-term abortions in Arizona are 
allowed only when the life or health of the mother is in danger. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Cuts Long-Distance Rates  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T is cutting prices for long-distance phone  
calls to 7 cents a minute in response to a price war with MCI 
WorldCom and Sprint. The new AT&AMP;T rate is good for calls made any 
time, with a $5.95 monthly fee. AT&AMP;T had charged 15 cents a minute 
around the clock with no monthly fee or 10 cents a minute with a 
$4.95 fee. MCI offers weekend and weekday nighttime rates of 5 
cents a minute, but daytime fees go up to 25 cents a minute. Its 
monthly fee, though, is $1.95. Sprint charges 5 cents per minute 
for nighttime calls for $5.95 a month, with rates going up to 10 
cents a minute for other calls. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were up 10.76 to 11,100.93. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 781-681. The Nasdaq was up 3.91 to 2,762.81. 

</P>
<P>
	Kenyan Admits Fixing Track Race  
</P>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Kenyan track star Bernard Barmasai lost  
his shot at a share of the $1 million Golden League jackpot today 
for saying he had colluded with a countryman to determine the 
result of a race. Track and field's ruling body ruled Barmasai put 
``athletics into disrepute'' by saying he had asked fellow Kenyan 
Christopher Koskei not to challenge his lead late in the 
3,000-meter steeplechase at the Aug. 11 Weltklasse meet in Zurich, 
Switzerland. Barmasai had been one of four athletes still in 
contention for the Golden League jackpot, which is split among 
those who go unbeaten through the seven biggest Grand Prix meets on 
the circuit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  



  	   	
</P>
