<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed Arco, BP Amoco Merger Ok'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Atlantic Richfield Co. shareholders on Monday  
approved the company's proposed merger with BP Amoco, a deal that 
would create the world's second-largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of BP Amoco were scheduled to meet Wednesday in  
London to consider the $29 billion acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives of Arco and BP Amoco agreed last April to the merger,  
which still must be approved by the Federal Trade Commission and 
the European Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Arco shareholders will receive .82 BP Amoco American Depository  
share for each share of Arco. 
</P>
<P>
	Arco, battered by more than a year of record-low crude oil  
prices, began looking for a merger partner last year. The company 
began negotiating with BP Amoco in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``BP Amoco's scale and financial strength will significantly  
enhance the value of Arco's assets and allow greater value to be 
realized than if Arco remained an independent oil company and gas 
company,'' Mike Bowlin, Arco's chairman and chief executive, told 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco executives have said they expect the deal to bring  
about $1 billion a year in cost savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Arco stock fell 25 cents to close at $86.12 1/2 on the New York  
Stock Exchange, while BP Amoco shares were unchanged at $110.37 1/2. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
