<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Woos New Hampshire Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN, N.H. (AP) -- Rural New Hampshire business leaders told  
Bill Bradley on Monday that the government should do more to help 
workers who have not benefitted from the country's recent economic 
prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes later, the Democratic presidential candidate was across  
town, sitting on a stack of hemlock two-by-fours at a sawmill and 
delivering the same message. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't be pleased about an economy that's growing unless it  
helps people all over the country,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like northern New York, Maine and Vermont, northern New  
Hampshire's economy has struggled this decade under the waning 
influence of the pulp and paper industries. New England mills, 
using outdated equipment, must compete with companies in Brazil, 
Finland and Japan that turn out paper more quickly and under fewer 
environmental regulations, said Preston Gilbert, executive director 
of the economy-minded North Country Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he wants to help the region adjust to a new,  
information-based economy -- possibly with the establishment of a 
regional development authority that would cross state lines. 
</P>
<P>
	John Simpson, a northern New Hampshire industry analyst with the  
state Department of Resources and Economic Development, said the 
North Country does not have the roads or infrastructure needed to 
attract and keep businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way we can financially keep up,'' Simpson said.  
``We don't even have the same capacity as the southern part of our 
own state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government can help by getting the big things right, Bradley  
said: balancing the budget, keeping international trade open, 
having the lowest tax rates for the most people, and spending money 
on education and research. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley did at least as much listening as talking, taking  
questions from high school basketball players in Groveton and about 
30 workers at White Mountain Lumber in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign spokesman Tony Wyche said Bradley has been trying to  
win support by showing voters respect. 
</P>
<P>
	The method -- and the message -- are working, said Randy Lawrence  
of Berlin, an employee of White Mountain Lumber. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made more sense than the other ones, the other  
candidates,'' Lawrence said. ``He sounds pretty good to me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
