<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 00:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Seek Reason for Crane Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Federal officials want to know why and how  
contractors were using a crane-hoisted platform that held three 
workers killed when another crane collapsed at the Milwaukee 
Brewers' future stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called ``man basket'' held the three ironworkers near the  
stadium roof when the accident happened July 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The 567-foot crane, called Big Blue, collapsed when it was  
trying to lift a 400-ton section of roof in place at the unfinished 
stadium, called Miller Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulations of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration  
strongly discourage the use of man baskets, but don't ban them, the 
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported in a story for Monday's 
editions. 
</P>
<P>
	The use, position and other details of the man basket that held  
the three workers who died are under investigation, George Yoksas, 
area administrator of OSHA, said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking at the propriety of that,'' Yoksas said.  
</P>
<P>
	Under OSHA rules, the baskets can be used only if alternatives  
are considered more hazardous or impossible to use ``because of 
structural design or work site conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alternatives include ladders, hoists, aerial lift trucks and  
elevated work platforms, according to OSHA. 
</P>
<P>
	Man baskets were the only practical way for workers to help  
direct the placement of stadium roof panels, said Franklyn Gimbel, 
a lawyer for Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of America, the stadium 
roof contractor. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Gimbel said there was no call to abort the lift by the  
three workers killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Violation of the OSHA rule on man baskets carries fines of  
$7,000 to $70,000. Yoksas said he had reached no conclusions yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoksas said OSHA would not have a report on the causes of the  
accident in the next few weeks, despite earlier indications that it 
might. He said he could give no time frame for release of any 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	By law, OSHA must release a report within six months of an  
accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
