<DOCNO> APW19990830.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 16:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cocaine Seized in Fish Shipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Nearly 3,000 pounds of cocaine was discovered  
hidden beneath a shipment of iced fish filets from Ecuador, and 
customs officials say it may be another inside smuggling job at 
Miami International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arrow Air cargo flight landed early Monday from Guayaquil,  
Ecuador, with 50 cardboard boxes. An estimated 2,720 pounds of 
cocaine, worth an estimated $21 million, was wrapped neatly in 
waxed paper packages hidden beneath filets of grouper, congrio and 
tuna. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs showed up in an X-ray during a routine inspection.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have reasons to believe people at the airport may have been  
involved,'' said customs agent John Clark. ``With that much cocaine 
and nobody coming to claim it, especially at that hour, it 
indicates to us that whoever is involved knew about the seizure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The seizure comes less than a week after 58 people were charged  
with smuggling drugs and weapons at the airport, many of whom 
worked for American Airlines. Clark did not say the two incidents 
were linked, but said there were similarities. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was charged, though the investigation was continuing.  
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Miami-based Arrow Air, Inc. said it has often  
been an active partner with the customs service in thwarting 
smugglers. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
