<DOCNO> APW19990830.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dennis Batters N.C. Coastline  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C. (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis has begun veering  
seaward while drenching North Carolina's coastline with rain and 
92-mph winds, knocking out power to upwards of 50,000 people. At 
noon EDT, Dennis was centered 90 miles southeast of Cape Lookout, 
or 105 miles east of Wilmington, and was moving toward the 
east-northeast at about 15 mph. Its maximum sustained wind blew at 
about 100 mph. Two people were killed in a head-on collision blamed 
on the wind and rain about 7:30 a.m. in the coastal Onslow County 
community of Richlands. Southport received 8 inches of rain, 
according to the National Hurricane Center. 

</P>
<P>
	East Timorese Vote on Independence  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Thousands of East Timorese cast their  
ballots today on whether to remain under Indonesian rule or gain 
independence. U.N. officials estimated that 90 percent of 
registered voters cast ballots. Although U.N. officials said the 
voting was relatively peaceful, a member of the U.N. team 
overseeing the election, Joel Lopez Gomes, was killed on his way 
home from a polling station. Indonesia invaded East Timor nearly a 
quarter-century ago, after Portugal ended a reign of nearly 400 
years. Human rights groups claim 200,000 people have died in the 
ensuing violence. 

</P>
<P>
	CDC: Decline in AIDS Deaths Slowing  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The sharp decline in AIDS deaths that began two  
years ago with the development of powerful new drugs has suddenly 
been cut in half, raising questions about whether the medications 
are already losing their punch, health officials said today. AIDS 
killed 17,047 people in the United States last year -- a decline of 
20 percent from 1997. From 1996 to 1997, the drop in deaths was a 
much more dramatic 42 percent, which health officials attributed to 
the effectiveness of new drugs. The CDC listed several possible 
causes for the slowdown in reductions of AIDS deaths, including the 
patients' failure to keep up with their medication. 

</P>
<P>
	Army May Change 'Dated' Ad Campaign  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army might change its well-known slogan  
``Be all that you can be'' as it looks for new ways to get young 
people to tune in to its recruitment efforts. The Army is studying 
a number of alternatives to recover from what has been the worst 
recruiting year since 1979, an Army spokesman said. The slogan has 
been used by the Army since 1981. But the spokesman stressed that 
the Army doesn't blame the slogan, and acknowledged that the good 
economy and the fact that more young people are going to college 
after high school are bigger factors for the falloff. 

</P>
<P>
	Crew Warns of Possible Mir Accident  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Members of the Mir's last full-time crew warned  
today that the Russian space station may spin out of control now 
that they have left it unmanned. The crew was not replaced because 
the cash-starved Russian government has said it could no longer pay 
for the 13-year-old Mir's operation. But instead of bringing the 
Mir down with the crew, space officials decided to leave it 
orbiting the Earth in hopes that they can find private funds to 
keep it aloft. Failing that, Russia plans to gradually lower the 
craft, then allowing it to burn up in the atmosphere, with it 
remnants ending up in the Pacific Ocean. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey Says Job Prospects Are Good  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new survey suggests U.S. demand for workers is  
continuing at the highest level in two decades, with employment 
especially strong in the wholesale and retail trades in advance of 
Christmas. A quarterly survey of some 16,000 companies by Manpower 
indicated that 30 percent planned further hiring in the 
October-December quarter. Just 8 percent anticipated cutbacks, 
while 58 percent said they expected no change. The findings by 
Manpower suggest that strong job creation should continue to hold 
U.S. unemployment in check. The nation's unemployment rate has been 
at or below 4.5 percent for more than a year, the best showing in 
three decades. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 105  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 105.12 to 10,985.05. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,886-865. The Nasdaq was down 37.91 to 
2,720.99. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Open Gets Under Way  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. Open, tennis' last major tournament of  
the season, is under way today. The opening match in Arthur Ashe 
Stadium saw 10th-seeded Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, the 1994 U.S. Open 
winner, eliminating Australian teen-ager Jelena Dokic, a qualifier 
who surprised top-seeded Martina Hingis in the first round at 
Wimbledon. In the men's draw, top-seeded Pete Sampras is going for 
his fifth U.S. Open title and a record 13th Grand Slam tournament 
title. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
