<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dennis Turns Out to Sea  
</P>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina residents breathed a sigh  
of relief as Hurricane Dennis turned out to sea today. ``We are 
hoping it continues that offshore track,'' said Jim Jones, 
spokesman for the state Division of Emergency Management. The 
shoreline was visited by 112 mph gusts and a deluge that flooded 
streets and left tens of thousands without power. Two traffic 
deaths early today were blamed on the storm. At 8 p.m., Dennis was 
120 miles east of Cape Hatteras, moving toward the east-northeast, 
but a hurricane warning remained in effect for most of the North 
Carolina coastline. 

</P>
<P>
	CDC: Decline in AIDS Deaths Slows  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The drop-off in AIDS deaths since the  
introduction of powerful drug cocktails has slowed dramatically, 
raising questions about whether the combination of medicines is 
reaching the limits of what it can do. Statistics released today at 
the first national conference on AIDS prevention showed that the 
decline in deaths slowed to 20 percent from 1997 to 1998, as 
compared to a 42 percent drop from 1996 to 1997. The CDC blamed the 
slowdown on a lack of treatment for some, the difficulty others 
have in sticking to the complicated regimen of pills, and the 
emergence of drug resistant strains of the virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Assembly Shuts Down Venezuelan Congress  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A constitutional assembly made up of  
supporters of Venezuela's President Hugo Chavez voted to usurp the 
Congress' few remaining powers, effectively shutting down the 
nation's legislature. The assembly said it took the action because 
Congress was interfering with the assembly's main work: writing a 
new constitution for Venezuela and reforming corruption-riddled 
public institutions. Opposition lawmakers said it was a move by 
President Hugo Chavez, the leader of a 1992 coup attempt, to amass 
political power. 

</P>
<P>
	Mideast Accord Said To Be Near  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- With pressure mounting for a deal before this  
week's arrival of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, 
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators said Monday they were on the 
verge of agreement on the long-delayed Wye River peace accord. But 
in a development that could complicate negotiations, the bodies of 
an Israeli couple were found in a forest on the border with the 
West Bank on Monday. Police suspected they were killed by 
Palestinians, raising worries of a resurgence of anti-Israeli 
violence. 

</P>
<P>
	House Subpoenas Waco Documents  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee today subpoenaed records for  
its investigation of the FBI's admission that incendiary tear gas 
canisters were used in the government's fiery 1993 standoff with 
the Branch Davidians. Congressional Republicans are incensed over 
the FBI's about-face last week after years of claims that only 
non-burning tear gas was used in the final hours of the deadly, 
51-day siege. Attorney General Janet Reno and the FBI have said 
there is no evidence that the incendiary devices lobbed at a 
concrete bunker 40 yards from the Davidians' compound ignited the 
fire that later raced through the wooden structure. 

</P>
<P>
	East Timor Votes on Independence  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Independence activists claimed victory  
Monday in a referendum on East Timor's future, buoyed by long lines 
of voters who defied the threat of violence against the 
U.N.-sponsored balloting. But official results will not be known 
for days. Voters chose between seceding or becoming an autonomous 
region within Indonesia. U.N. officials estimated that more than 90 
percent of 451,000 voters cast ballots. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Are Off  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell on Tuesday following weakness  
on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 122.27 points to 17,796.70 in early 
trading. In New York, the Dow ended down 176.04 at 10,914.13. It 
has fallen oven 100 points in each of the last three sessions. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi, Rios Advance at US Open  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There were no early surprises at the U.S. Open  
on the men's side as No. 2 Andre Agassi, winner of the French Open 
and runner-up at Wimbledon, showed he's ready to contend for a 
second U.S. title, rolling to a 6-0, 6-1, 6-3 victory over Nicklas 
Kulti. Others who advanced to the second round were No. 3 Yevgeny 
Kafelnikov, No. 8 Carlos Moya, No. Marcelo Rios and No. 12 Richard 
Krajicek moved into the second round. On the women's side, Martina 
Hingis raced through the first set, then survived three breaks of 
her service in the second set to beat No. 74-ranked Czech Kveta 
Hrdlickova 6-1, 7-5. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
