<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shares Grow After IAAF Cuts Barmasai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Kenyan steeplechaser Bernard Barmasai's  
disqualification from the Golden League on Monday could mean a 
bigger payday for the three remaining contenders when track action 
resumes this week. 
</P>
<P>
	American sprinter Marion Jones, 800-meter record-holder Wilson  
Kipketer of Denmark, and distance runner Gabriela Szabo of Romania, 
stand to benefit the most from the International Amateur Athletic 
Federation's decision to make Barmasai ineligible for the $1 
million Golden League jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
	With only two of seven Golden League meets remaining -- in  
Brussels on Wednesday and Berlin on Sept. 8 -- the jackpot is 
currently shared by the trio. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, however, is not expected to compete in Brussels after  
being forced out of last week's world championships when back 
spasms caused her to collapse to the track in her 200-meter 
semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly, Szabo and Kipketer stand to split the $1 million  
bonus. The jackpot is shared among athletes who remain unbeaten in 
the seven Golden League events. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining contenders were guaranteed bigger pieces of the  
pie Monday when the IAAF ruled Barmasai brought the sport ``into 
disrepute'' by saying he asked countryman Christopher Koskei not to 
challenge his lead late in the 3,000-meter steeplechase at the 
Weltklasse meet in Zurich, Switzerland on Aug. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw he was trying to pass me. I said `leave it for me,' and  
that's why he slowed down,'' Barmasai said at a press conference 
following his win. He also hinted that, if successful in his quest, 
he would share the winnings with Koskei. 
</P>
<P>
	Koskei denied hearing Barmasai speak to him, adding it would be  
impossible to speak at that stage in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF decided to allow Barmasai to continue to race on the  
Golden League circuit but make him ineligible to share in the 
season-ending jackpot. This means that Barmasai, who has won all 
five of his Golden League races so far, would remain empty-handed 
even if he wins his final two events. 
</P>
<P>
	The sport's world governing body also considered stripping  
Barmasai of his victory in the race but let the result stand, 
seeing no evidence of wrongdoing on a video replay. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the video you don't see Barmasai ever trying to speak to  
Koskei,'' IAAF spokesman Giorgio Renieri said. ``They are never 
within two meters of each other and it would be impossible for them 
to speak. An agreement would have been impossible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in an audio tape recording of the victor's press conference,  
the Kenyan clearly stated that Koskei let him win, Renieri said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is for this statement and not because of an actual  
transgression on the track that Barmasai is being sanctioned, the 
IAAF said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is why he is being punished,'' Renieri said. ``What he  
says put athletics into disrepute. It gives the public the idea 
that some races can be fixed when this is not true. 
</P>
<P>
	``The code of conduct states that athletes who put the sport  
into disrepute can be sanctioned in some way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
