<HEADLINE> McLeodUSA Has $1 Billion Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- Independent telephone company  
McLeodUSA Inc. reached an agreement Monday with Forstmann Little &AMP; 
Co. to receive a $1 billion investment in exchange for 12 percent 
of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	McLeodUSA, which offers telecommunications services in 11 states  
and plans to expand to 10 more, said it will use proceeds from the 
investment to develop its fiber optic network and introduce new 
telecommunications and data services. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based Forstmann Little will buy its stake in  
McLeodUSA through convertible preferred stock, which carries a 3.5 
percent coupon and converts to common stock at $36.50. The 
investment firm can convert its stake to common stock after five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McLeodUSA's rose 4 percent on the news, jumping $1.25  
to $32.75 in trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of Monday's agreement, Theodore Forstmann, senior  
partner at Forstmann Little, will join the McLeodUSA board of 
directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark McLeod founded McLeodUSA in June 1991 after selling  
Telecom USA to MCI Communications for $1.25 billion in 1990. MCI is 
now part of MCI WorldCom Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cedar Rapids-based McLeodUSA, which employs 7,100, provides  
local telephone service to business and residential customers in 
competition with local Bell telephone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1978, Forstmann Little is a private investment firm  
that has invested more than $13 billion in 24 buyouts, including 
Gulfstream Aerospace Corp., General Instrument Corp., Yankee Candle 
Co. and Community Health Systems Inc. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
