<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CompUSA Makes Late Earnings Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- CompUSA announced the immediate layoffs of 1,800  
sales people Monday as it struggles to return to profitability amid 
declining prices for personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based retailer also reported that it lost money again  
in the quarter ended June 26, however, operating losses were less 
than Wall Street had expected -- $14.9 million, or 16 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call had estimated the company would  
lose 24 cents a share in the quarter. A year ago, the company lost 
19 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Jim Halpin acknowledged that the past year has  
been a difficult one for the chain but said he was pleased with 
progress of a company restructuring that was announced in June. 
</P>
<P>
	CompUSA is trying to shed its image as a PC store and become a  
consumer electronics destination, selling more handheld personal 
organizers, digital cameras and camcorders, DVDs and other consumer 
gear. 
</P>
<P>
	The shift was prompted by plummeting average prices for PCs. The  
company said its average sales price for desktop PCs dropped about 
7 percent in the most recent quarter, and the average sales price 
of notebook computers dropped more than 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of CompUSA closed down 50 cents, or 7 percent, to $6.68 3/4  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings report had been delayed nearly two weeks while the  
company finished details of several restructuring efforts, 
including the sales layoffs, which will be spread throughout the 
company's stores. They bring CompUSA's total job cuts since June to 
2,400, and Halpin said another 300 are imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs are part of an effort to move sales agents out of  
local stores to regional locations. The company said putting the 
agents in stores led to duplication in markets where the chain has 
more than one store. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts saw hopeful signs beyond the most recent quarterly  
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``With a company as much in transition as CompUSA is, what's  
important is the direction they're headed,'' said Harry Katica, an 
analyst for Prudential Securities. ``I think they're reacting 
appropriately to very difficult industry circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company has closed four stores and Halpin said another 10  
``marginal'' stores could be closed. ``We've told the store 
managers, 'Fix it or we're going to fix you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The retailer reported net sales in the fourth quarter of $1.46  
billion, up 23 percent over a year ago, but sales at stores open 
one year or more rose just 1 percent. Sales at former Computer City 
stores, which CompUSA acquired, are still lagging, company 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 1999 fiscal year, the company reported an operating loss  
of $54.2 million, or 50 cents per share, compared with operating 
income of $57.2 million, or 33 cents per share for fiscal 1998. 
Sales in stores open at least a year fell 3.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also said they hope to spin off an Internet  
subsidiary, CompUSA Net.com Inc., first with a private offering and 
later a public offering. Halpin said the company will retain 
majority interest in the Internet operation even after a public 
sale of stock. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Lower Overall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) --Plans for a major French supermarket merger pushed  
the European retail sector higher, but shares overall were lower 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed down  
0.4 point at 314.57, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which 
tracks 297 companies in countries joining the single currency, 
ended down 0.6 point at 329.34. 
</P>
<P>
	French supermarket group Carrefour said Monday it was acquiring  
rival Promodes in a friendly stock deal that would create the 
world's second-largest retailer and a European counterweight to the 
biggest -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	France's CAC-40 index of most actively traded French stocks rose  
0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was regarded as likely to spur a wave of European  
mergers as Wal-Mart seeks to expand on the Continent and retailers 
look for partners. The news had a strong ripple effect throughout 
Europe's retailing sector. Stocks soared as investors tried to 
guess which store operators would consolidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Spain's largest listed supermarket groups -- Centros  
Comerciales Continente and Centros Comerciales Pryca -- closed 
strongly higher on the news that their French parents are to merge. 
Pryca rose 12.1 percent while Continente rose 12.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger's effects were also felt in Italy, where retailer  
Rinascente closed up 2.1 percent. Ifil, the Agnelli family's 
holding company, which owns 51 percent of Eurofind, which in turn 
owns 60 percent of Rinascente, was unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Metro, Germany's largest retailer, was the biggest gainer on the  
DAX index with a 2.2 percent rise. 
</P>
<P>
	One decliner was Dutch retailer Ahold, which would lose its  
number one ranking in Europe after the French merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index finished down 15.7 points at  
3,837.8, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 14.1 points at 
3,775.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Among domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra Dax closed down 27.83  
points, or 0.5 percent, at 5,392.53, while Amsterdam's AEX ended 
down 0.53 points at 584.36 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan's MIB30 index of blue chips closed at 3,4371, down 0.5  
percent, or 170 points, while the broader Mibtel fell 0.4 percent, 
or 87 points, at 23,984. 
</P>
<P>
	Madrid's IBEX-35 closed down 0.5 percent, or 52.20 points, at  
10,006.20. London's market was closed for a bank holiday. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
