<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell sharply Tuesday morning,  
weighted down by a decline on Wall Street and further weakness in 
the dollar against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 287.72 points,  
or 1.61 percent, to 17,631.25 at the end of the morning session. On 
Monday, the average closed up 319.60 points, or 1.82 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 110.78 yen, down 0.26 yen from late Monday in  
Tokyo but higher than its late New York level of 110.73 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices started lower as  
investor sentiment was damped by another fall in New York and the 
weaker dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average lost 176.04 points to close  
Monday at 10,914.13, declining for the third consecutive session. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Japanese economic report showing worse-than-expected  
industrial production figures was also weighing on Japanese stock 
prices, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ministry of International Trade and Industry said production  
fell 0.6 percent in July from June after adjustment for seasonal 
factors. Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires had projected 
on average that industrial output would be up 0.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 5.90 points, or 0.39 percent, to 1,492.04. 
The TOPIX closed up 19.56 points, or 1.32 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved as high as 110.95 yen  
early in the session after the Japanese government released the 
industrial output data. 
</P>
<P>
	But the greenback's gains were quickly pared on expectations the  
yen will strengthen as Japan's overall economy heads for recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.16 yen, up from  
116.09 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.9500 percent from Monday's finish of 1.9850 percent, driving 
its price up to 99.58 yen from 99.29 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
