<HEADLINE> Forbes To Run Anti-Gore Ad in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes  
began airing a radio commercial Monday that criticizes Vice 
President Al Gore's role in U.S.-Russia relations and demands an 
apology to Americans for sending U.S. aid to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Russia remains an economic and political time bomb,'' says an  
announcer. ``Immediately block all foreign aid to Russia until her 
workers are paid and root out the corruption of Russia's robber 
barons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Vice President Gore and Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers  
owe the American taxpayer an apology'' for foreign aid sent to 
Russia, says the ad, running this week in the upstate New York area 
where President Clinton is vacationing with his wife, Hillary 
Rodham Clinton, and their daughter, Chelsea. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad decries Mafia influence on the nation's finances that  
cost Russian workers wages. In addition to U.S. aid, it attacks 
lending by the International Monetary Fund, which the United States 
could prevent. It contends such aid could be diverted to illegal 
uses. 
</P>
<P>
	Another ad the Forbes campaign released Monday focuses on the  
recent $792 billion tax cut plan approved by Congress. Forbes 
encourages President Clinton to follow Congress' lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sign the tax cut, Mr. President,'' Forbes says. ``I would.''  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes campaign officials have said in the past that the  
campaign is spending $10 million on nationwide ads this summer. A 
spokesman said that these ads are part of that spending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
