<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thais See 3 Pct. GDP Growh for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's economy and currency, which  
triggered Asia's financial crisis, will grow stronger in 2000 after 
recovering this year, economic ministers were told Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Economic and Social Development Board, a state  
planning agency, forecast gross domestic product would grow by 3 
percent in 2000. The International Monetary Fund has predicted 
growth of between 3 and 4 percent for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile the baht should trade at between 36 and 37 to the U.S.  
dollar next year, compared with the current exchange rate of 38.3 
baht to the dollar, the NESDB said. 
</P>
<P>
	Predictions of sustained growth follow two years of sharp  
contraction after the onset of the crisis in mid-1997, when the 
baht was floated and plunged from 26 to the dollar to as low as 56 
in early 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking after the economic ministers' meeting, government  
spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart said the board expected consumer 
prices, a benchmark measure of inflation, to grow by 3 percent next 
year, compared with 0.5 percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Thailand should have a trade surplus in 2000 equal to 5 percent  
of GDP and a current account surplus of $8.2 billion, the board 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
