<HEADLINE> Bengals' Moore Can Walk With Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Cincinnati Bengals safety Kelvin Moore is able  
to get out of his hospital bed and walk with help from physical 
therapists as he recovers from a broken bone in his neck, the team 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, 24, sustained the career-threatening injury Aug. 20 at  
Pontiac, Mich., as he tackled a Detroit Lions player in a preseason 
game. The injury was diagnosed as a fractured vertebra in his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	He is recuperating at the University of Southern California  
Hospital in Los Angeles, near his family home, and is expected to 
remain at the hospital for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore has feeling in his arms and legs and is expected to make a  
full recovery, said Dr. Robert Heidt Jr., the Bengals' team 
physician. It is not known whether Moore will ever play football 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Bengals placed him on injured reserve. Cincinnati  
signed Moore in 1998 as a rookie free agent from Morgan State. He 
spent most of the season on the practice squad, but saw limited 
action in the Bengals' final four games. 
  	   	
</P>
