<DOCNO> APW19990830.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 17:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loftin's Dream Comes Crashing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- All Ryan Loftin ever wanted was to play  
football for Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	When Iowa didn't offer him a scholarship, Loftin joined the team  
as a walk-on. He endured a year as practice fodder for the varsity, 
stuck with it, earned a scholarship and eventually became a starter 
at defensive end. It was a textbook case of hard work being 
rewarded -- until it all came crashing down. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Loftin, whose scholarship was lifted earlier this month,  
stands accused of extortion for allegedly threatening to expose 
NCAA rules violations and provide information on the team to Iowa 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what's going on,'' Ron Book, who was Loftin's  
football and track coach at Waukee High School, said Monday. ``I 
would like to think it's not true. It just doesn't make sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Iowa defensive coordinator Bob Elliott also is puzzled.  
Elliott, who coached the Hawkeyes' defensive ends, saw Loftin work 
his way through the ranks to become a player good enough to start 
all 11 games last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did it through hard work and being a reliable guy,'' said  
Elliott, now an assistant to the athletic director at Iowa. ``The 
way he came is a very difficult row to hoe. He was a good team guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed it's happened like this, that it went  
this far,'' Elliott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Loftin was charged with extortion, a felony punishable by up to  
five years in prison and a $7,500 fine, and fifth-degree theft, a 
misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	According to charges filed by the Johnson County attorney's  
office, first-year Iowa coach Kirk Ferentz received a letter signed 
by Ryan Loftin that threatened to expose NCAA rules violations and 
share information about the football team to opponents if Loftin's 
scholarship was not restored. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter also said other disgruntled former players would be  
enlisted to generate negative publicity about Ferentz and the 
football program. 
</P>
<P>
	The theft charge alleges that Loftin took notebooks belonging to  
the athletic department. It is punishable by up to 30 days in jail 
and a $100 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Loftin, who had been listed as a second-team linebacker on the  
preseason depth chart, quit the team Aug. 17 and Ferentz lifted his 
scholarship. Three days later, Loftin called reporters to claim he 
had been run off and that Ferentz had violated NCAA rules by 
conducting mandatory offseason workouts, claims that Ferentz 
denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Loftin's attorney, Leon Spies, said his client would plead  
innocent. Spies also said he felt the case could have been handled 
without the filing of criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's devastating to any young person and that person's family  
to be charged with a felony regardless of the circumstances,'' 
Spies said. ``It just struck me this was a situation where some 
other creative avenues might have been explored by the university 
and they weren't. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not that Ryan is entitled to any better treatment than any  
other student, but if they really had his best interest at heart, 
some other approach might have been taken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spies said that perhaps Ferentz ``wanted to draw a line and make  
a statement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But it seems like it could have been done without involving  
the court system,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Loftin appeared before a magistrate Saturday morning and was  
released. He is to be arraigned on the theft charge Sept. 9. A 
preliminary hearing on the extortion charge is Sept. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret the whole thing,'' said Ann Rhodes, Iowa's vice  
president for university relations. ``I wish like crazy none of 
this would have happened. Personally, I'd like very much to stop 
talking about it, but this is where we are.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
