<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally mixed  
Monday, with prices surging in Tokyo and Hong Kong despite last 
week's slump on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
319.60 points, or 1.82 percent, to rebound from a four-day slump 
and close at 17,918.97. On Friday, the average fell 66.92 points, 
or 0.38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The buying spree in Tokyo came came after the Nikkei average had  
fallen a total of 634.18 points in the previous four trading days. 
</P>
<P>
	Short-term players bought actively, expecting that major local  
investment trusts will start buying Tuesday to set up funds 
totaling an estimated 60.0 billion yen ($541 million). 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar fell on selling by U.S.  
funds in the belief that U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan seemed concerned about stock values. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said on Frday that the extraordinary rise in U.S.  
stock prices over the last five years has been mostly inexplicable. 
Those remarks pushed the Dow Jones industrial average down 108.28 
points, or 1 percent, to close at 11,090.17 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 111.04 yen, down 0.40 yen from late  
Friday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 111.56 
yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks surged Monday following news that the territory  
has pulled out of a deep recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 305.53 points, or 2.3 percent, to 13,688.66. On 
Friday, the index had slumped 225.25 points, or 1.67 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said prices were boosted by Friday's announcement that  
Hong Kong's economy grew by 0.5 percent in the second quarter, 
surpassing expectations of private economists who had been 
predicting shrinkage of 1 to 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, that some investors remained cautious  
about the prospects of the Hong Kong market following Friday's 
slump on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares closed lower in thin and cautious trading,  
with attention focused on East Timor as the province votes to 
decide on its future. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's main main Composite Index fell 1.1  
percent, or 5.997 points, to 566.670. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices also slumped, dragged down by worries over the  
banking sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand, or SET, index fell 11.06  
points,l or 2.4 percent, to 446.48. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares closed lower on concerns about reforms in the  
financial industry after an offical said that the South Korean 
government may not be able to conclude a deal to sell a controlling 
stake in Seoulbank to Britain's HSBC Holdings PLC. The Korea 
Composite Stock Price Index fell 17.71 points, or 1.8 percent, to 
942.57. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed generally mixed. The market's key  
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 17.39 points, or 0.2 percent, to 
8,071.36. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares closed higher. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 7.94 points, or 0.3 percent, to 
2,155.31. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine share prices closed lower as investors  
continued to unload their holdings in anticipation of higher 
domestic interest rates. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange 
Index fell 20 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,201.24. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower, dragged down by  
Friday's weakness in U.S. markets. The All Ordinaries Index closed 
at 2993.0, down 27.2 points, or 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher as  
government-linked funds bought stocks on the last trading day 
before the Sept. 1 anniversary of capital controls. The benchmark 
Composite Index rose 2.27 points, or 0.2 percent, to 767.06. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower on profit-taking. The  
benchmark Straits Times Index fell 3.25 points, or 0.2 percent, to 
2,151.38. 
  	   	
</P>
