<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Abdullah al-Baradouni    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Abdullah al-Baradouni, Yemen's most famous  
poet, who was blinded as a child and later imprisoned several times 
for his politically charged writings, died Monday of a heart 
attack. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Baradouni started out as a teacher of Arabic literature and  
political history. He was blinded at the age of six after 
contracting small pox. 
</P>
<P>
	He served time behind bars in the 1950s, '60s and '70s for poems  
that criticized rulers during that period, including religious 
leaders and the military revolutionaries who overthrew them in 
1962. 
</P>
<P>
	The poet published 12 poetry books and six others on politics,  
literature and folklore. Many of his works were translated into 
foreign languages. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Waldo E. Cohn    	
</P>
<P>
	OAK RIDGE, Tenn. (AP) -- Waldo E. Cohn, a biochemist who helped  
build the world's first nuclear bomb during the Manhattan Project 
and who developed radioactive radioisotopes used as medical 
tracers, died Friday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Manhattan Project in 1942 while at the  
Metallurgical Laboratory at University of Chicago. At Oak Ridge the 
following year, he applied a technique known as ion exchange 
chromatography to the process of splitting uranium atoms to create 
plutonium. 
</P>
<P>
	For that, Cohn received the Chromatography Award of the American  
Chemical Society and was named a fellow of the American Academy of 
Arts and Sciences. 

</P>
<P>
                         *William A. Niering    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW LONDON, Conn., (AP) -- William A. Niering, professor of  
botany at Connecticut College and an internationally recognized 
wetlands expert, collapsed and died shortly after giving a lecture 
at the school Monday. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Niering helped lay the groundwork for the passage of  
Connecticut's Tidal Wetlands Act of 1969. In 1996, he received the 
Governors Environmental Award. 
</P>
<P>
	The author of six books, Niering was a founder and director of  
the Goodwin-Niering Center for Conservation Biology and 
Environmental Studies. He also served on the National Wetlands 
Technical Council. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Julius Parker    	
</P>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Julius Parker, former city editor and  
columnist for the Chattanooga Free Press, died Friday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Free Press, now the Chattanooga Times and  
Chattanooga Free Press, as a staff writer in 1948. He covered the 
General Assembly from 1953 to 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker became city editor emeritus in the mid-1990s and still  
came into the office regularly to write his column until ill health 
overtook him. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker is survived by his wife, Betty Parker, two sons and five  
grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                   *Louise Alone Thompson Patterson    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Louise Alone Thompson Patterson, a civil rights  
and labor activist from the Harlem Renaissance who was dubbed 
``Madame Moscow'' as a force in America's communist movement, died 
Friday. She was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	She taught school in Arkansas before moving to New York,  
spearheading various actions on behalf of blacks and working 
people. In that capacity, she traveled to Moscow and later, to 
Spain during the civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	By the 1930s, she was dubbed ``Madame Moscow'' as a founder of  
the left-wing group called the Vanguard, which was run out of her 
Harlem apartment and sponsored discussions on Marxist theory, 
theater performances, dances and concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1949, Mrs. Patterson helped organize the infamous Paul  
Robeson concert in Peekskill, N.Y., that ended in a violent riot. 
She also organized Robeson's national tour of black communities 
after he was blacklisted during the McCarthy era. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband, William Patterson, was a prominent communist  
activist who organized the Civil Rights Congress and was jailed for 
contempt of Congress by McCarthy after refusing to give the names 
of the group's supporters. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Patrick Rance    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Patrick Rance, a writer and merchant who  
championed traditional British farmhouse cheesemakers and crusaded 
for raw-milk cheeses, died Aug 22. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Rance leaves behind two influential works -- 1982's Great British  
Cheese Book -- which brought to the public attention clothbound, 
handmade cheese at a time when plastic-sealed, pasteurized cheese 
was proliferating -- and 1989's The French Cheese Book, the result 
of six years of research. 
</P>
<P>
	After serving in World War II, Rance married Janet Maxtone  
Graham and, together, they decided to buy a village shop in 
Streatley, near Henley-on-Thames. 
</P>
<P>
	When they first took it over in 1954, the shop stocked three  
cheeses: Dutch Edam, New Zealand Cheddar and Danish Blue. By 1980, 
the number had risen to 150. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Joanne Rodman    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLINGBORO, N.J. (AP) -- Joanne Rodman, a former editor and  
feature writer whose career at the Burlington County Times spanned 
three decades, died Aug. 23. She was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	A cause of death was not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	Rodman joined the newspaper in 1960 and wrote under the byline  
Joanne Schwartz. She served as Woman's Page editor and a feature 
writer. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, she was awarded an honorable mention for distinguished  
service to the mentally impaired through sports for a feature 
article about a local Special Olympics gold medal winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman is survived by her sons, Bart Zigler, James Zigler and a  
stepson, Kim Schwartz; her stepfather, Sidney Allinson, and four 
grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Marvin Sands    	
</P>
<P>
	CANANDAIGUA, N.Y. (AP) -- Marvin Sands, who developed a bulk wine  
company into the nation's second-largest supplier of wine, died 
Saturday of cancer. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Canandaigua Brands Inc., based in the Rochester suburb of  
Fairport, makes and distributes more than 150 brands of wine, beer 
and spirits. It is second in size only to E&AMP;J Gallo. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1945, Sands took over the operation of a bulk wine supplier  
in Canandaigua that had been purchased by his father. That business 
took off in 1954 when he introduced a successful sweet wine called 
Richard's Wild Irish Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Canandaigua bought Tenner Bros. Winery in South  
Carolina and the Hammondsport Wine Co. Other acquisitions included 
Bisceglia Brothers in California, Manischewitz Kosher Wines and 
Widmer Wines. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Fritz Shurmur    	
</P>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Fritz Shurmur, Seattle Seahawks defensive  
coordinator and the architect of the Green Bay Packers' defense 
that dominated the league in 1996, died Monday of esophageal and 
liver cancer. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was in his 20th year as an NFL defensive coordinator. He  
followed Mike Holmgren to Seattle in January when Holmgren was 
hired as the Seahawks' coach and GM. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur spent five seasons with the Packers and was instrumental  
in the team's run to consecutive Super Bowl appearances. He also 
served as a defensive coach with the Phoenix Cardinals, the Los 
Angeles Rams, the New England Patriots and the Detroit Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur joined the Packers in 1994, replacing current Green Bay  
head coach Ray Rhodes as defensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur was known as a defensive innovator and a premier teacher  
of the game. He wrote four books on defense and coached for his 
entire adult life, beginning in 1954 as a graduate assistant at his 
alma mater, Albion (Mich.) College. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a defensive coach at the University of Wyoming from  
1962-70 and head coach at the school from 1971-74. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Rev. J. C. Wade Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The Rev. J. C. Wade Sr., a civil-rights  
leader who built the largest predominately black congregation in 
Nebraska, died Monday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade, known as ``Daddy'' to his congregation, took over the  
250-member church in 1944. During his 44-year-tenure, the 
congregation expanded to 2,800 members. 
</P>
<P>
	A builder and innovator, Wade established a food pantry and  
oversaw the construction of two church buildings and a 50-unit home 
for the elderly that bears his name. He retired in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade also helped establish the Omaha Head Start program and the  
Omaha Opportunities Industrialization Center. He brought prominent 
leaders to Omaha, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson. He retired in 
1988. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Edgar Williams    	
</P>
<P>
	LANSDALE, Pa. (AP) -- Edgar Williams, a reporter and columnist at  
The Philadelphia Inquirer for more than 50 years who never lost his 
enthusiasm for writing and his interest in sports, died Sunday. He 
was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams spent much of his career at the newspaper writing about  
ordinary Philadelphians who normally wouldn't make it into the 
newspaper. He wrote a popular column, ``Nostalgia: Time, It Is 
A-Marching'' in addition to a Sunday Scene column. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote a sports column for The Reporter in his hometown  
of Lansdale as well as other articles for the Saturday Evening 
Post, Baseball Digest, Coronet and others. He co-authored the book 
``Around the World with the Harlem Globetrotters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While a teacher at Charlotte Hall Military Academy in Maryland,  
he coached the junior varsity football and baseball teams and was a 
sports correspondent for The Washington Post and The Baltimore Sun. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from the paper in 1989.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams is survived by his wife, Gladys Pike Williams; a  
daughter; a son; four grandchildren; and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                          *George M. Wilson    	
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- George M. Wilson, the Baptist layman who ran  
the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association's headquarters for 37 
years, died Tuesday. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson was business manager of the local Northwestern College  
while Graham was president, and then assumed the same task as 
executive vice president of the Graham association when it was 
founded in 1950 and set up shop in Minneapolis. He retired in 1987. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
