<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. Must Disclose Pension Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A company that is seriously considering  
improvements in its retirement plan must volunteer that information 
to employees who are considering retirement, a federal appeals 
court ruled Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a pair of 2-1 decisions, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals said an employer's duty to keep employees informed of their 
retirement options includes not only answering questions truthfully 
but also disclosing information without being asked. 
</P>
<P>
	The court reinstated suits by an Exxon employee and six Pacific  
Bell employees who said they would have delayed retirement if 
they'd been told the company was considering a sweetened retirement 
package. Their suits seek participation in the deals that were 
offered later. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1996, several appellate courts have ruled that companies,  
if asked, must disclose retirement improvements they were 
``seriously considering,'' a term that covers discussion by senior 
management with authority to implement the change. No previous 
appellate court had required a company to volunteer the 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	That's an important step, because ``if you don't know what's  
going on, how do you know to ask a question?'' said Thomas 
Moukawsher, lawyer for the former Exxon employee. He said his 
client, who worked on an oil drilling rig off the Southern 
California coast, was ``completely reliant on the chain of 
communications that the company had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Severson, lawyer for Exxon Co. U.S.A., said the ruling  
would create ``fertile ground for lawyers and litigants'' and 
confusion for employers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ernest Bins planned to retire from Exxon on Jan. 1, 1996 and  
heard rumors the company was planning to add a cash payment to its 
normal pension. He delayed his retirement date for a month and 
questioned several supervisors through late December but was told 
they knew nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Exxon U.S.A. had been studying the benefit increase as  
an incentive to early retirement for several months, the court 
said. The company president reviewed the proposal in mid-December, 
top executives of the parent Exxon Corp. reviewed and approved it 
in January, and it was formally announced less than two weeks after 
Bins retired. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit would have been worth an additional $35,000 or  
$40,000 to Bins, his lawyer said. His suit was dismissed by U.S. 
District Judge Harry Hupp of Los Angeles, who said the company had 
no duty to disclose its plans after Bins stopped asking. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Bell suit was filed by six employees who took early  
retirement in June 1995 after being told by managers that the 
company was in bad shape, planned layoffs and did not intend to 
make a better offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company actually had a healthy pension plan and was planning  
to offer an improved retirement plan to its union, the court said. 
The plan, adopted in August 1995, would have been worth between 
$27,000 and $99,000 to each of the six plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge William Enright of Los Angeles dismissed  
their suit, ruling that the company had not lied to them and that 
disclosure would have interfered with union negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court reinstated both suits, saying the companies  
were seriously considering the improvements before the employees 
retired and should have disclosed their plans, without making any 
guarantees. 
</P>
<P>
	A pension plan, which has the duty to protect its members'  
interests, must notify them of potential changes, rather than 
``penalizing a person who fails to ask the right questions at the 
right time,'' said Judge William Fletcher in the Exxon case. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are Bins vs. Exxon, 98-55662, and Wayne vs. Pacific  
Bell, 97-56456. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
