<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Market Said Needs Dose of Disbelief / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Perhaps it is true, as many Internet investors  
insist, that a new world of vast economic resources and riches lies 
ahead for those daring to believe. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Alan Greenspan, his ideology sown in what some think is the  
old world, has hinted that technological breakthroughs make him 
wonder if he can rely anymore on his old economic maps. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology of the information age, the new worlders assert,  
has made business more productive, creating value out of ideas 
rather than of iron, coal and brawn and vastly enhancing human 
wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of people -- inventors, entrepreneurs, investors,  
speculators, employees among them -- already have benefitted from 
their faith. And now, they say, the benefits will flow to all. 
</P>
<P>
	Ordinary people will be in constant communications via vest  
pocket electronic gadgets. Assembly lines will be run by electronic 
chips, freeing workers for more elevated, brainpower jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Business costs will be cut at every stage in production, meaning  
more revenue will fall directly to the bottom line. The economic 
pie will grow larger, enabling everyone to have a bigger slice. 
</P>
<P>
	And the threat of inflation, which has hung as heavily over  
progress as the plague in ancient days, will be greatly reduced. 
</P>
<P>
	If this sounds like Utopia, it may be. But, say the daring, the  
wealth of Utopia is already pouring in upon innovators and risk 
takers. Sometimes even in billion dollar amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	A billion dollars is a figure no human being can easily fathom  
in its full dimensions. It can't be spent. It is difficult even to 
give it away. Or, if someone were so disposed, to throw it away. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has been amassed, and quickly, by innovators selling  
shares in their companies. And thousands of lesser fortunes have 
been made by investors and employees who believed in them. 
</P>
<P>
	It's enough to make anyone wonder if there isn't something to  
the new world thesis. And to wonder also, as Greenspan has, if 
there isn't also reason to be fearful and cautious of lottery 
fever. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of investors already have expressed their belief in the  
new world by buying up shares in new world companies. Their 
pensions are so invested. Their savings. And their borrowings. 
</P>
<P>
	Is this inflation? Not as we used to think of it. It isn't the  
same as pushing up prices of items in the Consumer Price Index. But 
it is creating a wealth effect, which theoretically allows people 
to overspend and undersave. 
</P>
<P>
	And the consequences are different too: Stock prices can deflate  
as well as inflate (as may product prices), and the deflation can 
be catastrophic, affecting jobs, pensions, wages, profits, home 
equity values and ownership ... 
</P>
<P>
	And so, Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, is now more  
than ever inclined to examine stock prices as well as consumer and 
producer prices. And perhaps to discourage heavy investing by 
raising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We no longer have the luxury to look primarily to the flow of  
goods and services, as conventionally estimated,'' the chairman 
said in a speech late last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Now and in the future, he explained, the Fed must increasingly  
focus on changes in asset values in determining whether inflation 
is becoming a danger to the economy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 23:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
