<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 23:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Visit New York State Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton tapped the toe of his  
cowboy boot and looked a little out of sorts as the speakers at a 
New York political gathering took turns praising his wife and 
cheering on her presumed run for the Senate from their state. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he speaks warmly of her credentials and seems intrigued  
by the novelty of fostering a second politician in the family, the 
president is still new at the business of being a political spouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, it's pretty nice to go to a lunch like this when  
you're the only one who's not running for anything,'' Clinton joked 
at the beginning of his speech to farmers and politicos Monday at 
the New York State Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	In her speech, Hillary Rodham Clinton noted that ``there is not  
any place better'' to gauge public sentiment than a state fair. 
</P>
<P>
	The fair was the first stop for the Clintons in upstate New  
York, where they and their daughter, Chelsea, are ending a 16-day 
family vacation this week. The five-day leg will offer ample time 
for golf (the president) and glad-handing (the potential Senate 
candidate). 
</P>
<P>
	As they made their way from the fairgrounds to their borrowed  
lakeside estate in the well-heeled village of Skaneateles, 
reporters asked the president whether he is offering his wife tips 
on campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she's doing pretty well without any help from me,''  
Clinton replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has had plenty of help from her husband. Her  
vacation schedule in the Hamptons, Skaneateles and the rest of New 
York's Finger Lakes region and Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts 
included several fund-raisers for the Democratic party and Mrs. 
Clinton's senatorial exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Republicans outnumber Democrats at least two-to-one in  
this part of upstate, the Clintons got an enthusiastic welcome. 
Homemade signs offering greetings lined their motorcade route, and 
red, white and blue bunting cascaded from the fronts of charming 
Victorian houses in the Skaneateles village center. 
</P>
<P>
	En route to the vacation house, the first family stopped at a  
lemonade stand where two young boys waved a sign promising them 
free refreshments. 
</P>
<P>
	Up the road, three dozen people waited by the side of the road  
to greet the Clintons. After winding a little boy's camera to make 
sure he got the shot, the president finished shaking hands and 
stepped back to his bronze Suburban. 
</P>
<P>
	But the motorcade wasn't ready to roll. He waited, with his arms  
folded, his chin resting on his hand, watching his wife as she 
chatted with the young girls who stepped up to greet her and shook 
every last hand in the line. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he was proud, the president replied: ``Absolutely.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
