<DOCNO> APW19990830.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Cut Joe Patton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Joe Patton was his typical blunt self as he  
carried the big box with his belongings out the front door of 
Redskin Park on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a victim of double jeopardy, having fallen into disfavor  
with both the coach and the owner, and it just didn't make sense to 
him at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know this is a business move,'' Patton said. ``If you ask my  
opinion, it was a dumb business move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patton, the team's most versatile offensive lineman the last  
four years, and kicker Cary Blanchard were among 14 players cut 
Monday as the Washington Redskins trimmed their roster to 70 
players. Blanchard's release means Brett Conway has won the 
kicker's job. 
</P>
<P>
	On paper alone, Patton's release would be a mystery. He has  
started 54 games the last four years, including 37 at left tackle, 
the position responsible for protecting the quarterback's blind 
side. Five of his left tackle starts came in the second half of 
last season, when the Redskins finished strong. 
</P>
<P>
	The other left tackles on the roster are Andy Heck, an 11th-year  
veteran who's had back trouble and is the weakest starter on 
offense, and fifth-year player Kipp Vickers, who clearly was unable 
to match Patton during training camp. Shar Pourdanesh, who was 
splitting first-team work with Patton when camp began, was traded 
earlier this month after he became upset over his demotion to 
second team. 
</P>
<P>
	So why cut Patton? Coach Norv Turner, while conceding that  
Patton might be a better lineman than some he is keeping, cited 
``commitment,'' ``energy'' and ``attitude'' -- all of them lacking 
from a player who signed a five-year, $12.5 million contract in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you make that kind of commitment to a player, the player  
has to make that same kind of commitment to you, and it's got to be 
an every-day deal,'' Turner said. ``Those are a number of the 
conversations Joe and I have had over the last couple of years, 
about responsibility involved when you get to this level. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he understands where I'm coming from. It doesn't mean  
he agrees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patton has always been outspoken and opinionated, traits that  
usually don't sit well with Turner, and his offseason workouts 
haven't been the best. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw it coming way before you guys started talking about  
it,'' Patton said. ``I saw it coming because they had lack of 
confidence and lack of trust in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patton lost the starting job when he made a mental lapse on a  
blocking assignment in the exhibition opener against New England, 
allowing quarterback Brad Johnson to take a hard sack. The 
following week, new owner Dan Snyder referred to that play when 
asked which player was his least favorite Redskin. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner said Patton's release wasn't directly a result of that  
one play, and Patton seemed to agree. 
</P>
<P>
	``Snyder doesn't know everything he needs to know about this  
team yet,'' Patton said. ``And to go out and make a judgment about 
one player ... I'm not calling Mr. Snyder dumb, but that comment -- 
he didn't know me and had never met me. You have to look over stuff 
like that and go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Patton's best friend, Tre Johnson, there's the obvious  
concern: What happens if Heck's back gives out? How will Patton's 
release look then? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to hurt us,'' Johnson said. ``He made the  
mistake in the New England game, and allowed them to capitalize on 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also cut were receiver Kevin Alexander, running back Leroy  
Collins, punter Travis Colquitt, cornerback Buddy Crutchfield, 
linebacker Matt Finkes, receiver Junior Lord, receiver Kenny 
Mitchell, quarterback John Paci, safety Kevin Peoples, tackle Ozell 
Powell, defensive tackle Rod Walker and fourth-round draft pick 
Nate Stimson, who struggled to convert from defensive end to 
linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth-round draft pick Derek Smith, a tackle who injured his  
knee at the NFL combine, was placed on injured reserve. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 06:10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Pacific Buys Shoemaker Bally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Texas Pacific Group is buying  
shoemaker Bally from Oerlikon-Buehrle AG in a deal that is intended 
to revive Bally's slumping sales and profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal, announced Monday, were not released. The sale  
was expected to be completed by October. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Pacific, a private investment partnership based in San  
Francisco and Fort Worth, Texas, has a reputation for tightening 
financial controls and turning around declining consumer brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Pacific has broad portfolio of interests ranging from  
telecommunications and airlines to fashion firms and microchip 
makers. Its recent investments include U.S. clothing retailer J. 
Crew and Ducati, Italy's biggest motorcycle manufacturer 
</P>
<P>
	Bally, which was founded in 1851, manufactures fashion  
accessories and high-price shoes. It has been in long-term decline 
despite attempts by a succession of management teams to revive its 
fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 300 jobs in Switzerland have been eliminated since  
September 1997 as the company moved to restructure its business. 
The company made no mention of any further job losses and labor 
unions representing Swiss employees said they had heard of no 
planned cutbacks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 08:03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  East Timorese Vote on Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Throngs of East Timorese defied threats  
of violence to cast their ballots today in a U.N.-supervised 
referendum on independence after decades of Indonesian rule. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials hailed the huge, peaceful turnout. They estimated  
that 90 percent of registered voters cast ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	``The eagle of liberty has spread its wings over the people of  
East Timor,'' U.N. envoy Jamsheed Marker said in the provincial 
capital of Dili. He refused to speculate on the outcome, but said 
the voting was free and fair. The United Nations says it will need 
seven days to count and verify votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Optimistic independence supporters predicted that the enormous  
turnout meant success for their cause, allowing East Timor to break 
completely with Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are convinced that we have won because our people have  
suffered under Indonesia,'' said Leandro Isaac, a prominent 
independence leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite fears that many people would be too scared to vote, long  
lines formed outside polling centers. In many towns, enthusiastic 
voters scuffled to be the first to cast their ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrillas who have fought Indonesian troops for more than two  
decades walked out of the jungles carrying voter registration cards 
rather than guns. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Liquica, about 15 miles west of Dili, frightened  
villagers accused militiamen of threatening to burn their homes if 
they voted to break away from Indonesia, which invaded in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavily armed police who failed to rein in attacks by  
anti-independence militias stood guard, along with unarmed U.N. 
police advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded East Timor nearly a quarter-century ago, after  
Portugal ended a reign of nearly 400 years. Human rights groups 
claim 200,000 people have died in the ensuing violence. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 451,000 voters, including 13,000 East Timorese living  
abroad, registered for the ballot. They were asked if their 
impoverished, mainly Roman Catholic homeland should stay part of 
Muslim-dominated Indonesia as an autonomous region or break away 
completely. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-independence militiamen, accused of killing and terrorizing  
civilians to slash support for independence, said they would abide 
by the result that is to be announced by Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of people have been killed this year. An estimated 60,000  
have fled their homes in fear. Many traveled back to their 
shattered villages to cast votes. 
</P>
<P>
	There is overwhelming evidence that the military has backed the  
pro-Jakarta militias, though the government has consistently denied 
it. The armed forces have been reluctant to give up their hold on 
East Timor after nearly a quarter-century of a strong presence 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	The polls closed at 4 p.m., giving residents time to hurry home  
before nightfall and a possible new round of militia attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	In the town of Emera, 40 miles south of Dili, provocateurs fired  
gunshots before being dispersed by police. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. officer was injured in a shooting incident while helping  
monitor the referendum, Japanese Vice Foreign Minister Yutaka 
Kawashima said in Tokyo today. He provided no details. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, Indonesian Defense Minister and armed forces chief  
Wiranto said the military has the impression that the U.N. team 
carried out its duties very well. 
</P>
<P>
	``We consistently appeal to both sides to lay down their arms  
and surrender them to the Indonesian police,'' Wiranto said. He, 
like many Indonesians, uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	Sensing the overwhelming support for independence, a soft-spoken  
President B.J. Habibie went on national television Sunday night to 
appeal to East Timor's voters to remain a part of this sprawling 
nation of 210 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Separatist leader Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao called for a  
big turnout, then received a hero's welcome when he voted at the 
U.N. polling station in the Indonesian capital of Jakarta, where he 
is under house arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	A large crowd clapped and cheered when Timor's spiritual leader  
and 1996 Nobel Peace Prize winner, Bishop Carlos Belo, voted at a 
Dili schoolhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sydney, Jose Ramos Horta, who shared the Nobel prize with  
Belo, joined several hundred East Timorese refugees now living in 
Australia and New Zealand in casting his vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``For peace in Timor and all those who died in the past 23  
years,'' Ramos Horta said as he cast his ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Suharto, Indonesia's former authoritarian president who ordered  
the invasion, steadfastly ignored international opinion and refused 
to grant self-determination to the territory's 800,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	After Suharto was forced out last year, Indonesia agreed to  
allow the vote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990830.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 08:03:47 </DATE_TIME>
