<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More French Bank Restructuring Seen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Banque of France governor Jean-Claude Trichet said  
today that he expected further restructuring in France's banking 
sector in the wake of the merger of BNP and Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our banking sector restructuring is not complete,'' Trichet  
said in an interview with Europe 1 radio. ``There is still work to 
be done. We are going to continue with the sector restructuring 
calmly and with strength and hard work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trichet spoke two days after French banking regulators put an  
end to a six-month banking war by ruling that the BNP would not be 
allowed to keep its 37 percent minority stake in Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision left BNP with investment bank Paribas, while the  
isolated Societe Generale is now at the mercy of a foreign 
predator. In March, BNP had launched a hostile bid for Paribas and 
Societe Generale, which were in the midst of a friendly merger. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP's ambitious plan would have created Europe's biggest bank.  
Together with Paribas, BNP is now France's first bank and Europe's 
third in terms of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Trichet welcomed the BNP-Paribas merger, saying the new bank was  
``a tremendous project.'' He also stressed that ``Societe Generale 
is not for sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BNP chairman Michel Pebereau said in an interview published  
Sunday with the Journal du Dimanche that he did not plan to make a 
new run for Societe Generale and intended to focus on implementing 
the BNP-Paribas merger. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
