<HEADLINE> Vice President Cuts Vacation Short </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore and his family  
cut short their beach vacation as Hurricane Dennis bore down on the 
North Carolina coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gores left their borrowed Figure Eight Island home Sunday  
afternoon on the advice of military aides who talked with National 
Weather Service meteorologists, said Tommy Taft, a Greenville 
attorney and family friend. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't want to leave,'' Taft said. ``But with the weather  
deteriorating and with evacuation orders about to be posted, they 
made the decision to go back to D.C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president, his wife, Tipper, and a daughter, son-in-law  
and infant grandson arrived in Wilmington on Aug. 20 with plans for 
a 12-day vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gores had vacationed on the island for 10 days in 1997.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
